# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: broadside-naval
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:broadside-naval/74-gun] The **"seventy-four"** was a type of two-decked sailing ship of the line, which nominally carried 74 guns.
[src:broadside-naval/74-gun] It was developed by the French navy in the 1740s, replacing earlier classes of 60- and 62-gun ships, as a larger complement to the recently developed 64-gun ships.
[src:broadside-naval/74-gun] Impressed with the performance of several captured French seventy-fours, the British Royal Navy quickly adopted similar designs, classing them as third rates.
[src:broadside-naval/74-gun] The type then spread to the Spanish, Dutch, Danish and Russian navies.
[src:broadside-naval/74-gun] The design was considered a good balance between firepower and sailing qualities.
[src:broadside-naval/74-gun] Hundreds of seventy-fours were constructed, becoming the dominant form of ship-of-the-line.
[src:broadside-naval/74-gun] They remained the mainstay of most major fleets into the early 19th century.
[src:broadside-naval/74-gun] From the 1820s, they began to be replaced by larger two-decked ships mounting more guns.
[src:broadside-naval/74-gun] However, some seventy-fours remained in service until the late 19th century, when they were finally supplanted by ironclads.
[src:broadside-naval/74-gun] Standardising on a common ship size was an appealing ideal for naval administrators and bureaucrats.
[src:broadside-naval/74-gun] Although the seventy-four was a common type, the ship classes were not identical, even within the same navy.
[src:broadside-naval/74-gun] In the period 1750–1790, seventy-fours could measure from just under 2,000 to 3,000 tons burthen.
[src:broadside-naval/74-gun] The armament could also vary considerably, with the lower deck mounting 24-pounder to 36-pounder long guns, and a variety of calibres (sometimes including a few carronades) used on the upper deck.
[src:broadside-naval/74-gun] Some seventy-fours of the Danish navy only carried 70 guns.
[src:broadside-naval/74-gun] The first 74-gun ships were constructed by the French as they rebuilt their navy during the early years of the reign of Louis XV.
[src:broadside-naval/74-gun] The new ship type was a very large two-decker big enough to carry the largest common type of gun (36-pounders) on the lower gun deck, something only three-deckers had done earlier.
[src:broadside-naval/74-gun] This great firepower was combined with very good sailing qualities compared to both the taller three-deckers and the shorter old-style 70-gun two-deckers, making the 74 the perfect combination of the two.
[src:broadside-naval/74-gun] A disadvantage of the 74 was that it was relatively expensive to build and man compared to the older type of two-decker.
[src:broadside-naval/74-gun] The 74-gun ship carried 28 (24–36-pounder) long guns on the lower gun deck, 28–30 (18–24-pounders) on the upper gun deck, and 14–18 (6–12-pounders) on the upper works.
[src:broadside-naval/74-gun] Crew size was around 500 to 750 men depending on design, circumstances and nationality, with British ships tending to have smaller crews than other navies.
[src:broadside-naval/74-gun] The French had large and small seventy-fours, called *grand modèle* and *petit modèle*; the waterline length of a *grand modèle* seventy-four could be up to 182 feet.
[src:broadside-naval/74-gun] This was copied by the Royal Navy in about two dozen such ships of its own, such as HMS *Colossus* where they were known as Large, while the other seventy-fours built to be between 166–171 feet (51–52 m) were known as Common.
[src:broadside-naval/74-gun] The significance of the 74s is hard to overstate, as shown by a summary of the ships of the line for all nations that were in commission at any time during the Revolutionary/Napoleonic Wars period.
[src:broadside-naval/74-gun] Lengthening the hull by one gun port, allowing one additional gun per side on the lower and upper gun decks and on the quarterdeck produced the 80-gun ship.
[src:broadside-naval/74-gun] Given the construction techniques of the day, the seventy-four approached the limits of what was possible.
[src:broadside-naval/74-gun] Such long hulls made from wood had a tendency to flex and sag over time.
[src:broadside-naval/74-gun] Increased maintenance could counter this to some extent, but was of course costly.
[src:broadside-naval/74-gun] This limited the success of the even bigger two-deck 80-gun ships that were built in small numbers after the seventy-four had been introduced.
[src:broadside-naval/74-gun] Three-deckers did not have the same problem as the additional deck gave more rigidity.
[src:broadside-naval/74-gun] The Royal Navy captured a number of the early French 74-gun ships during the War of the Austrian Succession (for example, *Invincible*, captured at the first battle of Cape Finisterre in 1747) and the Seven Years' War and was greatly impressed by them compared to its own smallish 70-gun ships.
[src:broadside-naval/74-gun] As a result, it started building them in great numbers from about 1760, as did most other navies.
[src:broadside-naval/74-gun] Navies that were restricted by shallow waters, such as the Dutch and Scandinavian navies, at least early on tended to avoid the 74-gun ship to a certain degree due to its size and draught, preferring smaller two-deckers instead.
[src:broadside-naval/74-gun] Even so, the seventy-four was a standard feature in all European navies around 1800.
[src:broadside-naval/74-gun] Only a handful of 74-gun ships were commissioned into the United States Navy; the US Navy's early sea power concentrated on its frigates.
[src:broadside-naval/74-gun] The type fell into disuse after the Napoleonic Wars, when improved building techniques made it possible to build even bigger two-deckers of 84 or even 90 guns without sacrificing hull rigidity.
[src:broadside-naval/74-gun] The last seventy-four, the French Trafalgar veteran *Duguay-Trouin*, was scuttled in 1949.
[src:broadside-naval/74-gun] Her stern ornamentation is on display at the National Maritime Museum, Greenwich.
[src:broadside-naval/74-gun] In addition, dozens of ship models exist, produced as part of constructing the real ships, and thus believed accurate both externally and internally.
[src:broadside-naval/anthony-roll] The **Anthony Roll** is a written record of ships of the English Tudor navy of the 1540s, named after its creator, Anthony Anthony.
[src:broadside-naval/anthony-roll] It originally consisted of three rolls of vellum, depicting 58 naval vessels along with information on their size, crew, armament, and basic equipment.
[src:broadside-naval/anthony-roll] The rolls were presented to King Henry VIII in 1546, and were kept in the royal library.
[src:broadside-naval/anthony-roll] In 1680 King Charles II gave two of the rolls to Samuel Pepys, who had them cut up and bound as a single volume book, which is now in the Pepys Library at Magdalene College, Cambridge.
[src:broadside-naval/anthony-roll] The third roll remained in the royal collection until it was given by King William IV to his daughter Lady Mary Fox, who sold it to the British Museum in 1858; it is now owned by the British Library.
[src:broadside-naval/anthony-roll] The Anthony Roll is the only known fully illustrated inventory of ships of the English navy in the Tudor period.
[src:broadside-naval/anthony-roll] As the work of a successful state official in 16th-century England, the artistic value of the Anthony Roll has been described as being characterised by "naive draughtsmanship and conformity to a pattern" though its artistic aspects display "a decent amateur grasp of form and colour".
[src:broadside-naval/anthony-roll] While the inventories listed in its text have proven to be highly accurate, most of the ship illustrations are rudimentary and made according to a set formula.
[src:broadside-naval/anthony-roll] The level of detail of the ship design, armament and especially rigging has therefore proven to be only approximate.
[src:broadside-naval/anthony-roll] Nevertheless, through their depiction of the ceremonial ornamentation the illustrations in the Roll have provided relevant secondary information to the study of Tudor period heraldry, flags and ship ornamentation.
[src:broadside-naval/anthony-roll] The only known contemporary depictions of prominent Tudor era vessels like the *Henry Grace à Dieu* and the *Mary Rose* are contained in the Anthony Roll.
[src:broadside-naval/anthony-roll] As the *Mary Rose* sank by accident in 1545 and was successfully salvaged in 1982, comparison between the information in the Roll and the physical evidence of the *Mary Rose* has provided new insights into the study of the naval history of the period.
[src:broadside-naval/anthony-roll] In 1939 Dutch historian Nicholas Beets proposed that the Flemish artist and cartographer Cornelis Antoniszoon (or Antonisz., c.
[src:broadside-naval/anthony-roll] 1507–1553) could have been Anthony Anthony's brother.
[src:broadside-naval/anthony-roll] Although Beets' suggestion of kinship was conjectural and without any direct evidence, it was picked up by Geoffrey Callender in the *Mariner's Mirror* in 1963 and has been relayed by several other authors.
[src:broadside-naval/anthony-roll] The will of William Anthony did not mention any other sons and Anthonisz. is believed to have been the son of Antonis Egbertson, the daughter of Jacob Corneliszoon van Oostzanen.
[src:broadside-naval/anthony-roll] That Cornelis and Anthony were related is, in the words of Ann Payne, "not, presumably, impossible, but there is little evidence that they were connected at all".
[src:broadside-naval/anthony-roll] The "ship portrait" had a long history in maritime art, from medieval seals and coins to early engravings in the 15th century, and the plain side-on view of a ship under sail, often with no crew shown, was well established as the most effective way of recording the build of vessels.
[src:broadside-naval/anthony-roll] Contemporary maps, or "plats", were routinely decorated with detailed pictures of ships, to mark bodies of water as much as to liven up the scenes.
[src:broadside-naval/anthony-roll] Such maps were common at the time, and were even embellished by artists if deemed too simple or drab.
[src:broadside-naval/anthony-roll] This painting, recently dated to around 1545, has also been suggested as a likely source of inspiration to Anthony for his illustrations.
[src:broadside-naval/anthony-roll] There are three such plats depicting naval actions and expeditions that are attributed to Anthony: the route of Anne of Cleves from the Low Countries to England (1539), a French attack on a coastal fort (date unknown) and a French raid on Brighton (July 1545).
[src:broadside-naval/anthony-roll] The design of the ships in these paintings, especially that of the Brighton raid, closely match those in the rolls.
[src:broadside-naval/anthony-roll] It is not known exactly when work on the rolls began nor when it was finished.
[src:broadside-naval/anthony-roll] It is only certain that it was presented to the king the year it was dated, 1546.
[src:broadside-naval/anthony-roll] The inclusion of the *Mary Rose* that sank at the Battle of the Solent 19 July 1545 does not mean it was necessarily started before this date, since it was still considered possible that she could be raised even as late as 1549.
[src:broadside-naval/anthony-roll] The galleasses, the *Antelope*, *Hart*, *Bull* and *Tiger*, all present in the second roll, were still being built around March 1546, and the *Hart* was not at sea until October that year.
[src:broadside-naval/anthony-roll] At the same time the *Galley Blanchard*, captured from the French 18 May 1546 is not included.
[src:broadside-naval/anthony-roll] After the rolls were presented to the king they were archived in the royal collections.
[src:broadside-naval/anthony-roll] In 1680 Charles II gave two of the rolls to Samuel Pepys, a navy administrator and avid book collector.
[src:broadside-naval/anthony-roll] Pepys did not disclose the details of how the rolls were given to him, but it is believed that the gift came out of a meeting with King Charles where Pepys took down the king's account of how he escaped from the Battle of Worcester (1651).
[src:broadside-naval/anthony-roll] The plan was that Pepys would edit and publish the already famous story, but he never did so.
[src:broadside-naval/anthony-roll] It is also known that Pepys was planning to write a history of the navy and that he was gathering material for this task, but this project also was never finished.
[src:broadside-naval/anthony-roll] It is considered likely that King Charles was aware of Pepys' plans and presented him with two of the rolls either as a gift or as payment for the intended publication of the escape story.
[src:broadside-naval/anthony-roll] The second roll could not be located at that time, and it was not until 1690 that it was discovered by Henry Thynne, keeper of the royal library 1677–89 and a close friend of Pepys.
[src:broadside-naval/anthony-roll] Thynne arranged for Pepys to make copies of some of the illustrations, but by 1690 Charles was dead and James II was in exile.
[src:broadside-naval/anthony-roll] Pepys had resigned from his position as Secretary of the Admiralty that same year and refused to recognize the reign of William III and Mary II, which meant that acquisition of the final roll for his collection was out of the question.
[src:broadside-naval/anthony-roll] The creation of the codex from the first and third rolls is therefore assumed to have been completed shortly after that time.
[src:broadside-naval/anthony-roll] After Pepys' death in 1703 his library passed on to his nephew John Jackson.
[src:broadside-naval/anthony-roll] After the death of Jackson in 1724 the library, along with the codex, was then passed on to Pepys' old college at Magdalene, Cambridge, where it remains to this day.
[src:broadside-naval/anthony-roll] The second roll was presumed lost by the 1780s, but actually remained in the hands of the royal family.
[src:broadside-naval/anthony-roll] William IV gave it to his illegitimate daughter Mary FitzClarance sometime in the early 19th century.
[src:broadside-naval/anthony-roll] In 1824, FitzClarance married Charles Robert Fox, a major-general and from 1832–35 an officer of the surveyor of the ordnance, the same position Anthony Anthony had three centuries before him.
[src:broadside-naval/anthony-roll] Fox was a bibliophile, and historian Charles Knighton has suggested he knew the value of the roll, but its location nevertheless remained unknown to scholars.
[src:broadside-naval/anthony-roll] In 1857 Frederic Madden, keeper of manuscripts at the British Museum, was shown the second roll and learned that Mary Fox wished to sell it.
[src:broadside-naval/anthony-roll] After negotiations it was sold for £15 to the British Museum and was numbered Add MS 22047.
[src:broadside-naval/anthony-roll] It was kept in its original format as a roll and has been stored in the British Library's manuscript collection at St Pancras since 1999.
[src:broadside-naval/anthony-roll] The Anthony Roll has been used frequently as a primary source for histories of the English navy of the 16th century, but the full text and all illustrations were not collected in one volume until 2000.
[src:broadside-naval/anthony-roll] The Anthony Roll was originally a set of three separate vellum rolls.
[src:broadside-naval/anthony-roll] It exists today in the form of a bound volume containing the first and third rolls while the second roll is preserved in its original form.
[src:broadside-naval/anthony-roll] The three original rolls were made up out of a total of 17 individual membranes glued to the back of the next membrane.
[src:broadside-naval/anthony-roll] The membranes were of a width of 27+1⁄2 inches (70 cm) and a height varying from 31 to 37+3⁄4 inches (79 to 96 cm).
[src:broadside-naval/anthony-roll] After receiving the first and third rolls Pepys had his clerks cut the rolls up and bound in a single volume as a book, now known as **Pepys 2991**.
[src:broadside-naval/anthony-roll] The transformation of the two rolls created a horizontal page structure, and some of the ornamentation that was cut in process was copied into the volume by hand.
[src:broadside-naval/anthony-roll] Pepys also inserted abstracts between the two rolls and a summarizing table that was not Anthony's, but pre-dated Pepys' binding of the rolls.
[src:broadside-naval/anthony-roll] This radical treatment of the original document has damaged some of the illustrations and is today deprecated.
[src:broadside-naval/anthony-roll] The first three illustrations of the *Henry Grace à Dieu*, *Mary Rose* and *Peter Pomegranate* were all too large to fit on one page and were therefore converted to two-page spreads.
[src:broadside-naval/anthony-roll] The resulting bend down the centre of the illustrations led to noticeable loss of detail.
[src:broadside-naval/anthony-roll] Despite this, there are no plans to attempt a recreation of the original structure of the first and third rolls.
[src:broadside-naval/anthony-roll] The second roll, **British Library Add MS 22047**, is still in its original condition with the exception of a written endorsement by Mary Fox from 1857 and some damage caused by an application of chemicals to reveal faded writing.
[src:broadside-naval/anthony-roll] The three rolls list 58 ships divided into classes based roughly on size and construction.
[src:broadside-naval/anthony-roll] Each ship is presented along with its name, tonnage, crew size and, in Anthony's own words, "the ordenaunce, artillery, munitions and habillimentes for warre".
[src:broadside-naval/anthony-roll] The first roll lists the carracks and one pinnace, beginning with the largest ship *Henry Grace à Dieu*.
[src:broadside-naval/anthony-roll] The second roll lists galleasses, a hybrid of oar-powered and sailing vessels, and one galley.
[src:broadside-naval/anthony-roll] Finally, the third roll is reserved for pinnaces and "rowbarges", both basically smaller versions of galleasses.
[src:broadside-naval/anthony-roll] Anthony Anthony was not a trained, professional artist.
[src:broadside-naval/anthony-roll] The illustrations are described as "striking and boldly executed, but [...] have few claims to be fine works of art".
[src:broadside-naval/anthony-roll] The vessels are for the most part painted according to a standard formula, with distinct repetitions even in the more elaborate depictions.
[src:broadside-naval/anthony-roll] Anthony's style is signified by a "naive draughtsmanship and conformity to a pattern [...] consistent with the abilities of a government official with a decent amateur grasp of form and colour".
[src:broadside-naval/anthony-roll] The rolls were all of roughly the same length, about 15 feet (4.6 m), and would most likely have been presented side by side for display on a table or hung on a wall.
[src:broadside-naval/anthony-roll] The focal point of the whole composition is in the second, middle roll where the exceptionally well-executed painting of the *Galley Subtle* is placed.
[src:broadside-naval/anthony-roll] That this ship was intended to be the centrepiece illustration is made clear by the presence of the pinnace *Mary James* in the first roll, which is otherwise reserved for (sailing) ships.
[src:broadside-naval/anthony-roll] This appears to have originally been placed at the beginning of the third roll, among the other pinnaces and rowbarges, but was moved to achieve more equal lengths.
[src:broadside-naval/anthony-roll] In his pursuit of living up to the image of a Renaissance prince Henry is known to have been particularly fond of galleys, something which would have been known to Anthony.
[src:broadside-naval/anthony-roll] The lettering, framing lines and floral pattern decorations are painted in red or black with the exception of the first three ships of the first roll, which also feature gold.
[src:broadside-naval/anthony-roll] Most of the illustrations were first sketched with plummet outlines and were then painted over in washes.
[src:broadside-naval/anthony-roll] Ship timbers are a light brown that are shaded in the bow and stern to achieve depth, decorations and anchors are highlighted with red, and green is used for guns.
[src:broadside-naval/anthony-roll] Contours are in black and the sea is in shades varying from "greyish green" to "a richer blue".
[src:broadside-naval/anthony-roll] The first two rolls were done with roughly the same amount of detail while the lesser rowbarges (essentially small galleys) were done more hastily.
[src:broadside-naval/anthony-roll] The first two ships of the first roll, the *Henry Grace à Dieu* and the *Mary Rose*, have traces of a grid pattern, indicating that they were transferred from a different drawing while the rest are done in freehand.
[src:broadside-naval/anthony-roll] Overall, the ships follow a formula depending on the type of ship.
[src:broadside-naval/anthony-roll] The exceptions are stern galleries of some of the galleasses and the figureheads of the *Mary Rose*, *Salamander* and the *Unicorn*, the latter both captured from the Scots in 1544.
[src:broadside-naval/anthony-roll] The prominent exception is the *Galley Subtle* placed in the middle of the second roll.
[src:broadside-naval/anthony-roll] It is more consistent in type with Mediterranean-type galleys than the galleasses and small rowbarges, and features a considerable amount of detail not present in the other ships.
[src:broadside-naval/anthony-roll] It is the only ship where any crew is visible, in this case rowers behind pavisades as protection from enemy arrows and an overseer wearing "a bonnet, full skirted armorial doublet and baggy breeches" holding a stick or baton, as if beating the time of the strokes of the rowers.
[src:broadside-naval/anthony-roll] As a historical record, the Anthony Roll is in many ways unique.
[src:broadside-naval/anthony-roll] It is the only known fully illustrated list of a Tudor period royal navy, though the pictures should not be seen as exact depictions drawn from real life.
[src:broadside-naval/anthony-roll] For example, the lists of guns of the individual ships, which are considered to be an accurate record produced by a senior state official, are only approximately matched to the paintings.
[src:broadside-naval/anthony-roll] The rigging is only roughly accurate, and has been described by Margaret Rule, archaeological project leader of the *Mary Rose* excavations, as "a confusing assemblage of shrouds, ratlines and stays".
[src:broadside-naval/anthony-roll] Many details are present, but others are missing, such as the chain-wales (the horizontal platforms extending from the sides) to which the shrouds (the parallel ropes that stabilized the masts) were attached to keep them clear of the hull.
[src:broadside-naval/anthony-roll] Comparisons with the finds from the salvaged *Mary Rose* itself have provided an opportunity to compare the accuracy of the records provided in the Roll.
[src:broadside-naval/anthony-roll] The picture of the ship has provided clues about basic structural features, such as the number of masts and sails.
[src:broadside-naval/anthony-roll] When compared with an inventory of the ship from 1514, there is a close match, proving the illustration to be largely accurate.
[src:broadside-naval/anthony-roll] Examination of details in the construction, however, reveals that Anthony allowed himself some artistic licence.
[src:broadside-naval/anthony-roll] The armament in the painted ship appears clearly exaggerated.
[src:broadside-naval/anthony-roll] The heavy stern chasers (cannon placed in the stern aimed backwards) mounted through gun ports on the orlop deck, just about the waterline, would not have been feasible because of the lack of an orlop deck and the steep angle (sheer) of the ship in this area.
[src:broadside-naval/anthony-roll] The number of gunports in the broadside is inaccurate since it implies two slightly staggered rows of nine ports while the surviving starboard side of the *Mary Rose* has only one row of gunports on the main deck with seven ports.
[src:broadside-naval/anthony-roll] The accuracy of the forecastle has been more difficult to ascertain since none of it remains; conflicting interpretations of what it looked like have been suggested.
[src:broadside-naval/anthony-roll] The guns in the back of the forecastle have defied explanation, but one theory is that they were included to compensate for the guns that were positioned in the aftcastle, aiming forwards, but which would have been obscured due to the angle from which the ship was depicted.
[src:broadside-naval/anthony-roll] The list of ammunition, small firearms, longbows, arrows, pikes, and bills closely matches the archaeological evidence.
[src:broadside-naval/anthony-roll] As the source that is closest in time to the sinking of the *Mary Rose*, it has been of central importance for the archaeological project, especially in estimating the size of the crew.
[src:broadside-naval/anthony-roll] The Anthony Roll provides detailed information about the flags used on the ships.
[src:broadside-naval/anthony-roll] These feature a Saint George red cross on white ground on the hoist, nearest the flagpole, and a very long tail striped in green and white.
[src:broadside-naval/anthony-roll] They all feature gold paint on the red and green, and silver paint (now oxidized to black) on the white.
[src:broadside-naval/anthony-roll] This artistic device was used either to simulate the fluttering of the flags or to actually display the metallic thread and paint that was sometimes used to decorate them.
[src:broadside-naval/anthony-roll] The depictions of the flags and banners on the ships are in a heraldic and military sense considered to be roughly accurate but not entirely consistent.
[src:broadside-naval/anthony-roll] A kind of system of command among the various vessels is apparent in how flags are displayed on the masts, but it does not appear to have been carried through systematically.
[src:broadside-naval/anthony-roll] Some of the heraldic designs have been described as "unlikely" by the 20th century herald George Bellew, but have deemed to at least be "plausible" by Wilson.
[src:broadside-naval/anthony-roll] Rowbarge: A war galley or flat boat propelled by sails and rowing oars.
[src:broadside-naval/artillery-battery] The term is also used in a naval context to describe groups of guns on warships.
[src:broadside-naval/artillery-battery] Historically the term "battery" referred to a cluster of cannons in action as a group, either in a temporary field position during a battle or at the siege of a fortress or a city.
[src:broadside-naval/artillery-battery] Such batteries could be a mixture of cannon, howitzer, or mortar types.
[src:broadside-naval/artillery-battery] A siege could involve many batteries at different sites around the besieged place.
[src:broadside-naval/artillery-battery] The term also came to be used for a group of cannons in a fixed fortification, for coastal or frontier defence.
[src:broadside-naval/artillery-battery] During the 18th century "battery" began to be used as an organizational term for a permanent unit of artillery in peace and war, although horse artillery sometimes used "troop" and fixed position artillery "company".
[src:broadside-naval/artillery-battery] They were usually organised with between 6 and 12 ordnance pieces, often including cannon and howitzers.
[src:broadside-naval/artillery-battery] By the late 19th century "battery" had become standard mostly replacing company or troop.
[src:broadside-naval/artillery-battery] In the 20th century the term was generally used for the company level sub-unit of an artillery branch including field, air-defence, anti-tank and position (coastal and frontier defences).
[src:broadside-naval/artillery-battery] 20th-century firing batteries have been equipped with mortars, guns, howitzers, rockets and missiles.
[src:broadside-naval/artillery-battery] During the Napoleonic Wars some armies started grouping their batteries into larger administrative and field units.
[src:broadside-naval/artillery-battery] Groups of batteries combined for field combat employment called Grand Batteries by Napoleon.
[src:broadside-naval/artillery-battery] Administratively batteries were usually grouped in battalions, regiments or squadrons and these developed into tactical organisations.
[src:broadside-naval/artillery-battery] These were further grouped into regiments, simply "group" or brigades, that may be wholly composed of artillery units or combined arms in composition.
[src:broadside-naval/artillery-battery] To further concentrate fire of individual batteries, from World War I they were grouped into "artillery divisions" in a few armies.
[src:broadside-naval/artillery-battery] Coastal artillery sometimes had completely different organizational terms based on shore defence sector areas.
[src:broadside-naval/artillery-battery] Batteries also have sub-divisions, which vary across armies and periods but often translate into the English "platoon" or "troop" with individual ordnance systems called a "section" or "sub-section", where a section comprises two artillery pieces.
[src:broadside-naval/artillery-battery] The rank of a battery commander has also varied, but is usually a lieutenant, captain, or major.
[src:broadside-naval/artillery-battery] The number of guns, howitzers, mortars or launchers in an organizational battery has also varied, with the calibre of guns usually being an important consideration.
[src:broadside-naval/artillery-battery] In the 19th century four to 12 guns was usual as the optimum number to maneuver into the gun line.
[src:broadside-naval/artillery-battery] By the late 19th century, a mountain artillery battery was divided into a gun line and an ammunition line.
[src:broadside-naval/artillery-battery] The gun line consisted of six guns (five mules to a gun) and 12 ammunition mules.
[src:broadside-naval/artillery-battery] During the American Civil War, artillery batteries often consisted of six field pieces for the Union Army and four for the Confederate States Army, although this varied.
[src:broadside-naval/artillery-battery] Batteries were divided into sections of two guns apiece, each section normally under the command of a lieutenant.
[src:broadside-naval/artillery-battery] The full battery was typically commanded by a captain.
[src:broadside-naval/artillery-battery] Often, particularly as the war progressed, individual batteries were grouped into battalions under a major or colonel of artillery.
[src:broadside-naval/artillery-battery] In the 20th century it varied between four and 12 for field artillery (even 16 if mortars), or even two pieces for very heavy pieces.
[src:broadside-naval/artillery-battery] Other types of artillery such as anti-tank or anti-aircraft have sometimes been larger.
[src:broadside-naval/artillery-battery] Some batteries have been "dual-equipped" with two different types of gun or mortar, and taking whichever was more appropriate when they deployed for operations.
[src:broadside-naval/artillery-battery] From the late 19th century field artillery batteries started to become more complex organisations.
[src:broadside-naval/artillery-battery] First they needed the capability to carry adequate ammunition, typically each gun could only carry about 40 rounds in its limber so additional wagons were added to the battery, typically about two per gun.
[src:broadside-naval/artillery-battery] This in turn led to the need for signalers, which further increased as the need to concentrate the fire of dispersed batteries emerged and the introduction fire control staff at artillery headquarters above the batteries.
[src:broadside-naval/artillery-battery] Fixed artillery refers to guns or howitzers on mounts that were either anchored in one spot (though capable of being moved for purposes of traverse and elevation), or on carriages intended to be moved only for the purposes of aiming, and not for tactical repositioning.
[src:broadside-naval/artillery-battery] Historical versions often closely resembled naval cannon of their day, "garrison carriages," like naval carriages, were short, heavy, and had four small wheels meant for rolling on relatively smooth, hard surfaces.
[src:broadside-naval/artillery-battery] Later, both naval and garrison carriages evolved traversing platforms and pivoting mounts.
[src:broadside-naval/artillery-battery] Such mounts were typically used in forts, or permanent defensive batteries, such as coastal artillery.
[src:broadside-naval/artillery-battery] Fixed batteries could be equipped with much larger guns than field artillery units could transport, and the gun emplacement was only one part of an extensive installation that included magazines and systems to deliver ammunition from the magazines to the guns.
[src:broadside-naval/artillery-battery] Improvements in mobile artillery, naval and ground; air attack; and precision guided weapons have limited fixed position's usefulness.
[src:broadside-naval/artillery-battery] "Battery" is a relatively modern term at sea.
[src:broadside-naval/artillery-battery] Advanced warships in the Age of Sail, such as the ship of the line, mounted dozens of similar cannons grouped in broadsides, sometimes spread over several decks.
[src:broadside-naval/artillery-battery] This remained the standard main weapon layout for centuries, until the mid-19th century evolution of the naval rifle and revolving gun turrets came to displace fixed cannon.
[src:broadside-naval/artillery-battery] The first operational use of a rotating turret was on the American ironclad USS *Monitor*, designed during the American Civil War by John Ericsson.
[src:broadside-naval/artillery-battery] Open barbettes were also used to house their main batteries on rotating mounts.
[src:broadside-naval/artillery-battery] Both designs allowed naval engineers to dramatically reduce the number of guns present in the battery, by giving a handful of guns the ability to concentrate on either side of the ship.
[src:broadside-naval/artillery-battery] In time this trend reversed, with a proliferation of weapons of multiple calibers being arranged somewhat haphazardly about a vessel, many in mounts on the hull or superstructure with limited travel.
[src:broadside-naval/artillery-battery] Confusion also arose when combinations of large caliber "main battery" and smaller "secondary battery" weapons of mixed offensive and defensive use were deployed.
[src:broadside-naval/artillery-battery] This began to be resolved with the 1906 launching of the revolutionary "all big gun" battleship HMS *Dreadnought*.
[src:broadside-naval/artillery-battery] It shipped a main battery of ten heavy caliber guns, and a smaller secondary battery for self-defense.
[src:broadside-naval/artillery-battery] A third, or tertiary battery, of weapons lighter than the secondary battery was typically mounted.
[src:broadside-naval/artillery-battery] To simplify the design many later ships used dual-purpose guns to combine the functions of the secondary battery and the heavier guns of the tertiary batteries.
[src:broadside-naval/artillery-battery] Many dual-purpose guns also served in an anti-aircraft role.
[src:broadside-naval/artillery-battery] In addition, dedicated light-caliber rapid-fire anti-aircraft weapons were deployed, often in the scores.
[src:broadside-naval/artillery-battery] Conventional artillery as a vessel's battery has been largely displaced by guided missiles for both offensive and defensive actions.
[src:broadside-naval/artillery-battery] Small caliber guns are retained for niche roles, such as the multi-barrel Phalanx CIWS rotary cannon used for point defense.
[src:broadside-naval/artillery-battery] The rapid fire 5"/54 caliber Mark 45 gun 5-inch (130 mm) and Otobreda 76 mm (3.0 in) used for close defense against surface combatants and shore bombardment are among the last traditional naval guns still in use.
[src:broadside-naval/artillery-battery] In modern battery organization, the military unit typically has six to eight howitzers or six to nine rocket launchers and 100 to 200 personnel and is the equivalent of a company in terms of organisation level.
[src:broadside-naval/artillery-battery] In the United States Army, generally a towed howitzer battery has six guns, whereas a self-propelled battery (such as an M109 battery) contains eight.
[src:broadside-naval/artillery-battery] The battery is typically commanded by a captain in US forces and is equivalent to an infantry company.
[src:broadside-naval/artillery-battery] Other armies can be significantly different, however.
[src:broadside-naval/artillery-battery] The United Kingdom and Commonwealth forces have classified batteries according to the caliber of the guns.
[src:broadside-naval/artillery-battery] Headquarters batteries, which themselves have no artillery pieces, but are rather the command and control organization for a group of firing batteries (for example, a regimental or battalion headquarters battery).
[src:broadside-naval/artillery-battery] The basic field organization being the "gun group" and the "tactical group".
[src:broadside-naval/artillery-battery] The former being reconnaissance and survey, guns, command posts, logistic and equipment support elements, the latter being the battery commander and observation teams that deploy with the supported arm.
[src:broadside-naval/artillery-battery] In these armies the guns may be split into several fire units, which may deploy dispersed over an extended area or be concentrated into a single position.
[src:broadside-naval/artillery-battery] In some cases batteries have operationally deployed as six totally separate guns, although sections (pairs) are more usual.
[src:broadside-naval/artillery-battery] A battery commander, or "BC" is a Major (like his infantry company commander counterpart).
[src:broadside-naval/artillery-battery] However, in these armies the battery commander leads the "tactical group" and is usually located with the headquarters of the infantry or armoured unit the battery is supporting.
[src:broadside-naval/artillery-battery] Increasingly these direct support battery commanders are responsible for the orchestration of all forms of fire support (mortars, attack helicopters, other aircraft and naval gunfire) as well as artillery.
[src:broadside-naval/artillery-battery] General support battery commanders are likely to be at brigade or higher headquarters.
[src:broadside-naval/artillery-battery] The gun group is commanded by the Battery Captain (BK), the battery's second-in-command.
[src:broadside-naval/artillery-battery] However this position has no technical responsibilities, its primary concern is administration, including ammunition supply, local defence and is based in the "wagon-lines" a short distance from the actual gun position, where the gun towing and logistic vehicles are concealed.
[src:broadside-naval/artillery-battery] Technical control is by the Gun Position Officer (GPO, a lieutenant) who is also the reconnaissance officer.
[src:broadside-naval/artillery-battery] The battery has two Command Posts (CP), one active and one alternate, the latter provides back-up in the event of casualties, but primarily moves with the preparation party to the next gun position and becomes the main CP there.
[src:broadside-naval/artillery-battery] Each CP is controlled by a Command Post Officer (CPO) who is usually a Lieutenant, 2nd Lieutenant or Warrant Officer Class 2.
[src:broadside-naval/artillery-battery] Gun positions may be "tight", perhaps 150 m × 150 m (490 ft × 490 ft) when the counter battery threat is low, or gun manoeuver areas, where pairs of self-propelled guns move around a far larger area, if the counter-battery threat is high.
[src:broadside-naval/artillery-battery] During the Cold War NATO batteries that were dedicated to a nuclear role generally operated as "sections" comprising a single gun or launcher.
[src:broadside-naval/artillery-battery] Groupings of mortars, when they are not operated by artillery, are usually referred to as platoons.
[src:broadside-naval/artillery-battery] For example: the basic field organization being the "gun group" and the "tactical group".
[src:broadside-naval/artillery-battery] The former being reconnaissance and survey, guns, command posts, logistic, and equipment support elements, the latter being the battery commander and observation teams that deploy with the supported arm.
[src:broadside-naval/artillery-battery] It some cases batteries have operationally deployed as six totally separate guns, although sections (pairs) are more usual.
[src:broadside-naval/barrage-artillery] In military usage, a **barrage** is massed sustained artillery fire (shelling) aimed at a series of points along a line.
[src:broadside-naval/barrage-artillery] In addition to attacking any enemy in the kill zone, a barrage intends to suppress enemy movements and deny access across that line of barrage.
[src:broadside-naval/barrage-artillery] The impact points along the line may be 20 to 30 yards (18 to 27 m) apart, with the total line length of the barrage zone anything from a few hundred to several thousand yards long.
[src:broadside-naval/barrage-artillery] Barrages can consist of multiple such lines, usually about 100 yards (91 m) apart, with the barrage shifting from one line to the next over time, or several lines may be targeted simultaneously.
[src:broadside-naval/barrage-artillery] A barrage may involve a few or many artillery batteries, or even (rarely) a single gun.
[src:broadside-naval/barrage-artillery] Typically each gun in a barrage, using indirect fire, will fire continuously at a steady rate at its assigned point for an assigned time before moving onto the next target, following the barrage's detailed timetable.
[src:broadside-naval/barrage-artillery] Barrages typically use high-explosive shells, but may also be shrapnel, smoke, illumination, poison gas (in World War I), or potentially other chemical agents.
[src:broadside-naval/barrage-artillery] Barrages are in contrast with concentrated artillery fire, which has a single specific target such as a known enemy position or structure, and in contrast with direct fire which targets enemies within the direct line of sight of the gun.
[src:broadside-naval/barrage-artillery] Barrages may be used defensively or offensively, and have a variety of patterns.
[src:broadside-naval/barrage-artillery] Defensive ones are often static (such as a *standing* barrage) while offensive ones are moved in coordination with the advancing friendly troops (such as *creeping*, *rolling*, or *block* barrages).
[src:broadside-naval/barrage-artillery] They may target along the front line, or further into enemy back area to isolate certain enemy positions (such as a *box* barrage).
[src:broadside-naval/barrage-artillery] A series of different patterns may be employed as a battle develops, with each barrage lasting only a few minutes or many hours.
[src:broadside-naval/barrage-artillery] Barrages are usually integral with larger operations of multiple military formations, from divisions to armies, requiring days to weeks of preparation and exact planning.
[src:broadside-naval/barrage-artillery] The barrage was developed by the British Army in the Second Boer War.
[src:broadside-naval/barrage-artillery] It came to prominence in World War I, notably its use by the British Expeditionary Force and particularly from late 1915 onwards when the British realized that the suppressive effects of artillery to provide covering fire were the key to breaking into defensive positions.
[src:broadside-naval/barrage-artillery] By late 1916 the creeping barrage was the standard means of applying artillery fire to support an infantry attack, with the infantry following the advancing barrage as closely as possible.
[src:broadside-naval/barrage-artillery] Its employment in this way recognised the importance of artillery fire in suppressing or neutralizing, rather than destroying, the enemy.
[src:broadside-naval/barrage-artillery] It was found that a moving barrage immediately followed by the infantry assault could be far more effective than weeks of preliminary bombardment.
[src:broadside-naval/barrage-artillery] Barrages remained in use in World War II and later, but only as one of a variety of artillery tactics made possible by improvements in predicted fire, target location and communications.
[src:broadside-naval/barrage-artillery] The term *barrage* is widely – and technically incorrectly – used in the popular media for any artillery fire.
[src:broadside-naval/barrage-artillery] The moving barrage was developed during the Boer War, one of several tactical innovations instituted under command of General Redvers Buller.
[src:broadside-naval/barrage-artillery] It was a response to Boer defensive positions, notably at Tugela Heights and effective long range rifle fire.
[src:broadside-naval/barrage-artillery] Artillery usually fired over open sights at visible targets, until the Second Boer War when indirect fire started to be used.
[src:broadside-naval/barrage-artillery] The largest unit accustomed to firing at a single target was the brigade (i.e. an artillery battalion), normally 18 guns.
[src:broadside-naval/barrage-artillery] Trench warfare led to the necessity for indirect firing through the use of observers, more sophisticated artillery fire plans and an increasingly scientific approach to gunnery.
[src:broadside-naval/barrage-artillery] Gunners had to use increasingly complicated calculations to lay the guns.
[src:broadside-naval/barrage-artillery] Individual guns were aimed so that their fall of shot was co-ordinated with others to form a pattern; in the case of a barrage, the pattern was a line.
[src:broadside-naval/barrage-artillery] The term “barrage” was first used in World War I in English in the orders for the Battle of Neuve Chapelle in 1915.
[src:broadside-naval/barrage-artillery] A **lifting barrage** was a development in which the barrage lifted periodically to a target further back, such as a second line of trenches.
[src:broadside-naval/barrage-artillery] This was used during the first day of the Somme and it was countered by the defenders infiltrating troops and machine guns into no-man's land or the areas between their own trench lines, so it was found necessary to comb the entire area of the advance with artillery fire.
[src:broadside-naval/barrage-artillery] A **creeping barrage** (also called a **moving barrage**) was a barrage that lifted in small increments, usually 50 to 100 yards (46 to 91 m) every few minutes, moving forward slowly, keeping pace with the infantry.
[src:broadside-naval/barrage-artillery] British practice evolved to fire at two lines simultaneously.
[src:broadside-naval/barrage-artillery] Eventually, three patterns of advancing the barrage developed.
[src:broadside-naval/barrage-artillery] In a *creeping* barrage, the shell-fire moved from one line to the next.
[src:broadside-naval/barrage-artillery] In a *block* barrage two or more lines were fired on simultaneously and then the fire moved as block to the next lines to be engaged.
[src:broadside-naval/barrage-artillery] In a *rolling* barrage, the fire on the line nearest to their own troops moved to the first unengaged line behind then after a set interval the fire on the second line would move in turn to the next one behind that.
[src:broadside-naval/barrage-artillery] By late 1917, the technique of a *creeping* barrage had been perfected and could be made to move in complex ways, the barrage wheeling or even combing back and forth, to catch the defenders re-emerging after the barrage had passed but it was still governed by a timetable.
[src:broadside-naval/barrage-artillery] A creeping barrage that was too slow would risk friendly fire on one's advancing troops; too quickly could mean that the enemy would have too much time to emerge from cover to resume defensive positions and attack the exposed advancing troops.
[src:broadside-naval/barrage-artillery] After World War I the British developed the "quick barrage", a standard barrage pattern that could be ordered by radio without advance plotting of the fire plan on a map.
[src:broadside-naval/barrage-artillery] A **standing barrage** was static, and might be defensive, to inhibit the movement of enemy troops and break up attacks.
[src:broadside-naval/barrage-artillery] A creeping barrage could be made to stand on a line for a time before it moved on, perhaps waiting for the infantry to form up behind it, or to catch up, or perhaps it would stand on the line of known enemy defences, to do more damage and sap enemy morale.
[src:broadside-naval/barrage-artillery] The fireplan for the Battle of Messines on 7 June 1917 called for most of the British 18-pounder field guns to fire a creeping barrage of shrapnel immediately ahead of the advance, while the other field guns and 4.5-inch (110 mm) howitzers fired a standing barrage some 700 yards (640 m) ahead.
[src:broadside-naval/barrage-artillery] The standing barrage was aligned with known German positions, and lifted to the next target when the advance reached within 400 yards (370 m) of it.
[src:broadside-naval/barrage-artillery] As each objective was taken by the infantry, the creeping barrage would pause at 150 to 300 yards (140 to 270 m) ahead of them and become a standing barrage, protecting the newly gained positions from counter-attack while the infantry consolidated.
[src:broadside-naval/barrage-artillery] During this time the pace of fire slackened to one round per gun a minute, enabling the guns and the crews a respite before resuming full intensity as the barrage moved on.
[src:broadside-naval/barrage-artillery] The heavy and super-heavy artillery fired on German rear areas.
[src:broadside-naval/barrage-artillery] Over 700 machine guns participated in the barrage, using indirect fire over the heads of their own troops.
[src:broadside-naval/barrage-artillery] In a **box barrage** three or four barrages formed a box – or more often three sides of a box – around a position to isolate it.
[src:broadside-naval/barrage-artillery] Standing or box barrages were often used for defensive fire tasks, in which the barrage was registered beforehand on a position – agreed with the defending infantry commander – to be called down in the event of an enemy attack on his positions.
[src:broadside-naval/barrage-artillery] A box barrage could also be used to prevent the enemy from reinforcing a position to be attacked.
[src:broadside-naval/barrage-artillery] In a trench raid of March 1917, the 1st Battalion the Buffs were supported first by a creeping barrage, then by a box barrage once they were in the enemy trenches, to prevent German reinforcement or counter-attack.
[src:broadside-naval/barrage-artillery] It was aided with dummy bombardments on other sections of the line to confuse the enemy.
[src:broadside-naval/barrage-artillery] Ideally the attackers should be into the enemy positions before the defenders had time to recover their composure after the terror of an intense bombardment, emerge from shelters and man their firing positions.
[src:broadside-naval/barrage-artillery] On the First day of the Somme, and in the later French Nivelle Offensive on the Chemin des Dames, the barrage outpaced the infantry, allowing the defenders to recover and emerge from their dug-outs, with disastrous results for the attackers.
[src:broadside-naval/barrage-artillery] By the end of World War I it was realised that the important effect of the barrage was to demoralise and suppress the enemy, rather than physical destruction; a short, intense bombardment immediately followed by infantry assault was more effective than the weeks of grinding bombardment used in 1916.
[src:broadside-naval/barrage-artillery] A creeping barrage could maintain the element of surprise, with the guns opening fire only shortly before the assault troops moved off.
[src:broadside-naval/barrage-artillery] It was useful when enemy positions had not been thoroughly reconnoitred, as it did not depend on identifying individual targets in advance.
[src:broadside-naval/barrage-artillery] On the other hand, it was wasteful of ammunition and guns, as much of the fire would inevitably fall on ground containing no enemy.
[src:broadside-naval/barrage-artillery] The World War I barrage with programmed lifts had the effect of confining the infantry advance to the artillery schedule, and of requiring the use of linear tactics, restricting infantry manoeuvre.
[src:broadside-naval/barrage-artillery] The importance of the barrage was such that traditional infantry tactics, such as reliance on the infantry's own firepower to support its movement, were sometimes forgotten.
[src:broadside-naval/barrage-artillery] In the featureless Western Desert in World War II, one benefit of the barrage was that it enabled the infantry to conform their line to the barrage, ensuring that their line of advance was correct.
[src:broadside-naval/barrage-artillery] By 1943 the barrage was considered to dissipate firepower and to constrain the infantry into advancing in rigid lines.
[src:broadside-naval/barrage-artillery] A barrage could severely churn up the ground, especially in soft going, and impede the progress of the attacking troops.
[src:broadside-naval/barrage-artillery] It is sometimes claimed that creeping barrage was first used during World War I in the battle of Gorlice in May 1915 (part of the Gorlice–Tarnów offensive) by General Tadeusz Rozwadowski, but in fact infantry assault was simply preceded by a four-hour shelling of the Russian defences.
[src:broadside-naval/barrage-artillery] The first day of the battle of the Somme saw another attempt at a large-scale creeping barrage which had been planned in anticipation of the infantry's anticipated ability to advance relatively unhampered across the battlefield due to a heavy, week-long preparatory bombardment.
[src:broadside-naval/barrage-artillery] For example, on XV Corps front, the barrage was programmed to lift 50 yards (46 m) every minute.
[src:broadside-naval/barrage-artillery] Complications arose however in British protocols to prevent friendly-fire casualties which at the time dictated that shellfire was to be kept over one hundred yards (91 m) away from their own uncovered infantry.
[src:broadside-naval/barrage-artillery] In many cases no man's land was narrower than the allowable 'safe' distance and as such the barrage did not protect the men as they went 'over the top' and advanced towards the German trenches.
[src:broadside-naval/barrage-artillery] Further, as the British infantry was slowed far beyond the expected pace of advance across no-man's land, all along the Somme front it proved impossible for the infantry to keep up with the pace of the barrage.
[src:broadside-naval/barrage-artillery] However, the tactic was further refined as the Battle of the Somme wore on and by September 1916 the creeping barrage became a standard tactic for infantry attacks, and soon spread to the French Army, enabling the French recapture of Fort Vaux at the Battle of Verdun in November 1916.
[src:broadside-naval/barrage-artillery] A report said "Experience has shown that it is far better to risk a few casualties from an occasional short round from our own artillery than to suffer the many casualties which occur when the bombardment is not closely followed up".
[src:broadside-naval/barrage-artillery] A creeping barrage was essential to the success of the Canadian Expeditionary Force in the capture of Vimy Ridge in April, 1917.
[src:broadside-naval/barrage-artillery] The creeping barrage was used during the action of Tell 'Asur on 12 March 1918 in the Sinai and Palestine Campaign.
[src:broadside-naval/barrage-artillery] The creeping barrage moved at a rate of between 50 yards (46 m), 75 yards (69 m) and 100 yards (91 m) per minute.
[src:broadside-naval/barrage-artillery] At first, British creeping barrages consisted only of shrapnel shells but an equal mix of HE was soon added, in some cases later supplemented by smoke shells.
[src:broadside-naval/barrage-artillery] The creeping barrage would advance at a rate of 100 yards (91 m) every one to six minutes, depending on terrain and conditions; although six minutes was found to be too slow.
[src:broadside-naval/barrage-artillery] By the Battle of Arras in 1917, the creeping barrage was huge and complex, with five or six lines of fire covering a depth of 2,000 yards (1,800 m) ahead of the infantry.
[src:broadside-naval/barrage-artillery] Back barrages were fired, in which rearmost lines of the barrage reversed direction, and machine gun barrages were introduced.
[src:broadside-naval/barrage-artillery] False barrages attempted to deceive the enemy about Allied intentions or to force him to reveal his positions.
[src:broadside-naval/barrage-artillery] The creeping barrage was used to great effect in the Canadian success at the Battle of Vimy Ridge where the men had been extensively trained to move forward in the 'Vimy Glide' – a 100-yard per three minute pace (30 m/min) which kept the infantry directly behind the barrage.
[src:broadside-naval/barrage-artillery] The British barrage advanced 100 yards (91 m) every four minutes, with the infantry following as close as 50 yards (46 m) from the bursting shells.
[src:broadside-naval/barrage-artillery] One battery's programme required 45 lifts.
[src:broadside-naval/barrage-artillery] As each objective was reached, the barrage settled 500 yards (460 m) beyond the new position, combing back and forth to disrupt expected German counter-attacks, while some of the artillery moved forward to support the next phase of the advance.
[src:broadside-naval/barrage-artillery] On the Eastern Front, German Colonel Georg Bruchmüller developed a form of double creeping barrage, with the first line of the barrage consisting of gas shells.
[src:broadside-naval/barrage-artillery] His ideas were applied on the Western Front in the German spring offensive of 1918.
[src:broadside-naval/barrage-artillery] Once open warfare returned after the breaking of the Hindenburg Line in September 1918 the British fired far fewer creeping barrages, using more lifts and concentrations instead.
[src:broadside-naval/barrage-artillery] Attacks by tanks do not need the same form of artillery support, and the single barrage along the entire front of the advance had even been abandoned by the battle of Cambrai in 1917.
[src:broadside-naval/barrage-artillery] More sophisticated fire control enabled infantry to call down artillery fire in direct support, or targeting of identified enemy positions.
[src:broadside-naval/barrage-artillery] On 31 August 1918 the attack of the U.S.
[src:broadside-naval/barrage-artillery] 32nd Division was preceded by a walking barrage.
[src:broadside-naval/barrage-artillery] After first passing over the German line, the barrage returned twice more, attempting to catch the defenders returning to their firing positions from their dugouts, or to keep them underground when the real assault went in.
[src:broadside-naval/barrage-artillery] The barrage remained in use in World War II, but was no longer the dominant artillery plan.
[src:broadside-naval/barrage-artillery] In the absence of the huge set-piece infantry assaults of World War I, barrages were on a smaller scale.
[src:broadside-naval/barrage-artillery] For the opening of the second Battle of El Alamein, for example, a barrage was considered by British Lieutenant-General Bernard Montgomery's planners, but rejected in favour of fierce concentrations on known or suspected targets in turn.
[src:broadside-naval/barrage-artillery] Along a 12,000-yard (11,000 m) front, 456 guns were considered insufficient for a true creeping barrage (at Neuve Chapelle there had been one gun for every four yards of front).
[src:broadside-naval/barrage-artillery] But creeping and rolling barrages were used in some divisional sectors and in later phases of the Alamein battle.
[src:broadside-naval/barrage-artillery] For Operation Supercharge on 1–2 November 1942, the attack in the 2nd New Zealand Division sector was preceded by a creeping barrage of 192 guns along a 4,000-yard (3,700 m) front, firing on three lines.
[src:broadside-naval/barrage-artillery] There was almost one 25-pounder for every 20 yards of front, plus two medium regiments thickening the barrage.
[src:broadside-naval/barrage-artillery] By the fighting in Tunisia, more guns were available and the defenders were more concentrated than in the Western Desert.
[src:broadside-naval/barrage-artillery] The artillery plan for the British attack at Wadi Akarit in April 1943 involved eight barrages in three phases ahead of the advances of 50th (Northumbrian) and 51st (Highland) Infantry Divisions.
[src:broadside-naval/barrage-artillery] They included a standing barrage to mark the start line in the dark and enable the infantry to form up in the right alignment; a barrage that wheeled left during the advance; and an on-call creeping barrage.
[src:broadside-naval/barrage-artillery] Nevertheless, attacks rarely relied solely on a barrage for artillery support: at Wadi Akarit pre-arranged concentrations on likely targets were called down by observers in the course of the assault.
[src:broadside-naval/barrage-artillery] Nevertheless, it remained in use in the Italian Campaign.
[src:broadside-naval/barrage-artillery] In the assault on the Hitler Line during the Battle of Monte Cassino on 23 May 1944, 810 guns were amassed for the attack of I Canadian Corps.
[src:broadside-naval/barrage-artillery] Three hundred of them fired on the first line of a 3,200-yard (2,900 m) wide barrage, beginning three minutes before the infantry moved off and lifting at a rate of 100 yards in five minutes.
[src:broadside-naval/barrage-artillery] It was due to pause for an hour at the first objective, then lift at 100 yards per three minutes to the further objectives, but the timing was disrupted by heavy resistance and defensive artillery fire.
[src:broadside-naval/barrage-artillery] The operation was later criticised for concentrating on too narrow a front, constrained by the need for enough guns to produce a dense barrage.
[src:broadside-naval/barrage-artillery] On Monte Sole, U.S. artillery fired probably its heaviest barrage of the war, 75,000 shells in a half-hour to clear the advance of the South Africans.
[src:broadside-naval/barrage-artillery] During the Battle of Normandy, a creeping barrage fired from 344 guns preceded the opening attacks of 15th (Scottish) Infantry Division in Operation Epsom on 26 June 1944.
[src:broadside-naval/barrage-artillery] For the opening of Operation Veritable, the push to the Rhine, the fire of 1,050 field and heavy guns was supplemented by 850 barrels of *pepper-pot* barrage: other weapons – mortars, machine guns, tanks, anti-tank guns, anti-aircraft guns and rockets – supplementing the field guns.
[src:broadside-naval/barrage-artillery] The true barrage of the British XXX Corps began at 09:20, building in intensity over the next hour, 500 guns shooting at a line 500 yards deep.
[src:broadside-naval/barrage-artillery] The barrage included smoke shells to screen the attackers forming up behind the barrage.
[src:broadside-naval/barrage-artillery] From 10.30 the barrage was pure high explosive and began to roll forward.
[src:broadside-naval/barrage-artillery] A 300-yard lift was made every 12 minutes, the lifts being signalled to the infantry by yellow smoke shells, and the barrage paused for ½ hour at each defensive line.
[src:broadside-naval/barrage-artillery] 2,500 shells were fired per square kilometre per hour until the barrage stopped at 16:30.
[src:broadside-naval/barrage-artillery] The barrage remained in Soviet doctrine in World War II, where the creeping barrage by massed guns was the standard accompaniment to an infantry assault.
[src:broadside-naval/barrage-artillery] The Soviet artillery had plenty of guns.
[src:broadside-naval/barrage-artillery] Some 7,000 guns and mortars were massed for the counter-attack at the battle of Stalingrad, and huge bombardments remained standard for the rest of the war.
[src:broadside-naval/barrage-artillery] During the Soviet advances in 1944–45, the tactic was used extensively throughout the Eastern Front such as the Vyborg–Petrozavodsk Offensive, the Battle of the Seelow Heights, and the Battle of Berlin.
[src:broadside-naval/barrage-artillery] The barrage continued in use into the Korean War.
[src:broadside-naval/barrage-artillery] At the Battle of Pork Chop Hill, UN forces employed on-call, pre-registered defensive fires called *flash fire* to defend its outposts, in which artillery laid down a box barrage in a horseshoe-shaped pattern around the outpost.
[src:broadside-naval/barrage-artillery] In the 1982 Falklands War, the assault of 42 Commando Royal Marines on Mount Harriet was preceded by a moving concentration from supporting artillery, firing some 100 yards ahead of the advancing Marines.
[src:broadside-naval/barrage-artillery] Later phases of the attack used a pepperpot fire, including Milan anti-tank missiles.
[src:broadside-naval/barrage-artillery] However, neither of these were true barrages with fire aimed at successive lines to a strict timetable.
[src:broadside-naval/barrage-artillery] The term **Barrage** as a method of fire control was not included in the 1965 ABCA artillery agreement nor its successor NATO STANAG.
[src:broadside-naval/barrage-artillery] The word *barrage*, imported from the French for "barrier" around 1915, means a coordinated bombardment as a static or moving barrier, as described in this article.
[src:broadside-naval/barrage-artillery] The word has also entered general language, where it has come to mean any intense sequence of words or missiles – such as *a barrage of questions*.
[src:broadside-naval/barrage-artillery] Nowadays, any form of artillery fire of more than one round may be described as a barrage in general language.
[src:broadside-naval/barrage-artillery] Even military historians use it in a non-technical sense, referring to any intense artillery fire.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] A **battleship** is a large, heavily armored warship with a main battery consisting of large guns, designed to serve as a capital ship.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] From their advent in the late 1880s, battleships were among the largest and most formidable warship types ever built, until they were surpassed by aircraft carriers beginning in the 1940s.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] The modern battleship traces its origin to the sailing ship of the line, which was developed into the steam ship of the line and soon thereafter the ironclad warship.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] After a period of extensive experimentation in the 1870s and 1880s, ironclad design was largely standardized by the British *Royal Sovereign* class, which are usually referred to as the first "pre-dreadnought battleships".
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] These ships carried an armament that usually included four large guns and several medium-caliber guns that were to be used against enemy battleships, and numerous small guns for self-defense.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] Naval powers around the world built dozens of pre-dreadnoughts in the 1890s and early 1900s, though they saw relatively little combat; only two major wars were fought during the period that included pre-dreadnought battles: the Spanish–American War in 1898 and the Russo-Japanese War of 1904–1905.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] The following year, the British launched the revolutionary all-big-gun battleship HMS *Dreadnought*.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] This ship discarded the medium-caliber guns in exchange for a uniform armament of ten large guns.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] All other major navies quickly began (or had already started) "dreadnoughts" of their own, leading to a major naval arms race.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] During World War I, only one major fleet engagement took place: the Battle of Jutland in 1916, but neither side was able to achieve a decisive result.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] In the Interwar period, the major naval powers concluded a series of agreements beginning with the Washington Naval Treaty that imposed limits on battleship building to stop a renewed arms race.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] During this period, relatively few battleships were built, but advances in technology led to the maturation of the fast battleship concept, and several of these ships were built in the 1930s.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] The treaty system eventually broke down after Japan refused to sign the Second London Naval Treaty in 1936.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] Although the rise of the aircraft carrier during World War II largely relegated battleships to secondary duties, they still saw significant action during that conflict.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] Notable engagements include the battles of Cape Spartivento and Cape Matapan in 1940 and 1941, respectively; the sortie by the German battleship *Bismarck* in 1941; the Naval Battle of Guadalcanal in 1942; and the Battle of Leyte Gulf in 1944.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] After World War II, most battleships were placed in reserve, broken up, or used as target ships, and few saw significant active service during the Cold War.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] The four American *Iowa*-class battleships were reactivated during the Korean War in the early 1950s and again in the 1980s as part of the 600-ship Navy.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] Even at the height of their dominance of naval combat, some strategists questioned the usefulness of battleships.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] Beginning in the mid-1880s, the *Jeune École* (Young School) argued that construction of expensive capital ships should stop in favor of cheap cruisers and torpedo boats.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] Despite a period of popularity for the *Jeune École*, the idea fell out of favor and the battleship remained the arbiter of naval combat until World War II.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] Even afterward, they remained potent symbols of a country's might and they retained significant psychological and diplomatic effects.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] A number of battleships—predominantly American—remain as museum ships.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] A ship of the line was a large, unarmored wooden sailing ship which mounted a battery of up to 120 smoothbore guns and carronades, which came to prominence with the adoption of line of battle tactics in the early 17th century.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] From 1794, the alternative term 'line of battle ship' was contracted to 'battle ship' or 'battleship'.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] The sheer number of guns fired broadside meant a ship of the line could wreck any wooden enemy, holing her hull, knocking down masts, wrecking her rigging, and killing her crew.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] They also imparted a psychological effect on the crews of smaller vessels.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] Ships of the line were also fairly resilient to the guns of the day; for example, the British Royal Navy lost no first-rate (the largest type of ship of the line) to enemy action during the entire 18th century.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] Over time, ships of the line gradually became larger and carried more guns, but otherwise remained quite similar.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] Development of the first-rates was particularly conservative, as these ships represented a major investment.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] By the early 1800s, the traditional "seventy-four" (so-named because it carried 74 guns) was no longer considered to be a proper ship of the line, having been supplanted by 84- and 120-gun ships.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] The first major change to the ship of the line concept was the introduction of steam power as an auxiliary propulsion system.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] Steam power was gradually introduced to the navy in the first half of the 19th century, initially for small craft and later for frigates.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] Early vessels used paddle wheels for propulsion, but by the 1840s, the first screw propeller equipped vessels began to appear.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] The value of these smaller steam-powered warships demonstrated their worth, when vessels like the British *Nemesis* proved to be critical to the Anglo-French success in the First Opium War in the 1840s.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] The French Navy introduced steam to the line of battle with the 90-gun *Napoléon* in 1850—the first true steam battleship.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] *Napoléon*, which was designed by Henri Dupuy de Lôme, was armed as a conventional ship-of-the-line, but her steam engines could give her a speed of 12 knots (22 km/h; 14 mph), regardless of the wind.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] This was a potentially decisive advantage in a naval engagement.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] The introduction of steam accelerated the growth in size of battleships.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] France and the United Kingdom were the only countries to develop fleets of wooden, steam-screw battleships although several other navies operated small numbers of screw battleships, including Russia (9), the Ottoman Empire (3), Sweden (2), Naples (1), Denmark (1) and Austria (1).
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] Concurrent with the development of steam power, another major technological step heralded the end of the traditional ship of the line: guns capable of firing explosive shells.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] Pioneering work was done by the French artillery officer Henri-Joseph Paixhans beginning in 1809.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] The American artillerist George Bomford followed not far behind, designing the first shell-firing Columbiad in 1812.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] The British and Russians began to follow suit in the 1830s, though early smoothbore guns could not fire shells as far as solid shot, which hampered widespread adoption in any fleet.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] By the early 1840s, the French Paixhans gun and American Dahlgren gun had begun to be adopted by their respective navies.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] In the Crimean War of 1853–1855, six Russian ships of the line and two frigates of the Black Sea Fleet destroyed seven Turkish frigates and three corvettes with explosive shells at the Battle of Sinop in 1853.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] The battle was widely seen as vindication of the shell gun.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] Despite losing her bowsprit and her foremast, and being set on fire, she was ready for action again the very next day.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] As amply demonstrated at the Battle of Sinop, and again during the Anglo-French blockade of Sevastopol from 1854 to 1855, wooden ships had become vulnerable to shell-firing guns.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] This prompted the French emperor Napoleon III to order the first ironclad warships: the *Dévastation*-class ironclad floating batterys.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] Three of these ships led the Anglo-French attack on the Russian fortress on the Kinburn Peninsula in the Battle of Kinburn in 1855, where they bore the brunt of Russian artillery fire, but were not seriously damaged.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] The success of these ships prompted the French and British to order several similar vessels.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] In March 1858, the French took development of the ironclad to its next logical step: a proper, ocean-going armored warship.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] This vessel, another design by Dupuy de Lome, was *Gloire*, and after her launching in 1859, Napoleon III ordered another five similar ships, which sparked a naval arms race with Britain.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] The first French ironclads had the profile of a ship of the line, cut to one deck due to weight considerations.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] Although made of wood and reliant on sail for most journeys, *Gloire* and her contemporaries were fitted with screw propellers, and their wooden hulls were protected by a layer of thick iron armor.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] Britain responded promptly with *Warrior*, a similar but much larger ironclad with an iron hull.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] By the time *Warrior* was completed in 1861, another nine ironclads were under construction in British shipyards, some of which were conversions of screw ships of the line that were already being built.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] Spain and Russia ordered ironclads in 1861, as did the United States and rebel Confederate States of America after the start of the American Civil War.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] Construction of these large and expensive warships remained controversial until March 1862, when news of the Battle of Hampton Roads, fought between the Union USS *Monitor* and the Confederate CSS *Virginia*, firmly settled debate in favor of even larger construction programs.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] From the 1860s to 1880s, navies experimented with the positioning of guns, in turrets, central-batteries, or barbettes; ironclads of the period also prominently used the ram as a principal weapon.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] As steam technology developed, masts were gradually removed from battleship designs.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] The British Chief Constructor, Edward Reed, produced the *Devastation*-class ironclads in 1869.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] These were mastless turret ships, which adopted twin-screw propulsion and an arrangement of two pairs of 12-inch (305 mm) guns, one fore and one aft of the superstructure, that prefigured the advent of the pre-dreadnought battleship some two decades later.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] By the mid-1870s steel was used as a construction material alongside iron and wood.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] The French Navy's *Redoutable*, laid down in 1873 and launched in 1876, was a combination central battery and barbette ship, which became the first capital ship in the world to use steel as the principal building material.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] The rapid pace of technological developments, particularly in terms of gun capabilities and thickness of armor to combat them, quickly rendered ships obsolescent.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] In the continuous attempt by gun manufacturers to keep ahead of developments in armor plate, larger and larger guns were fitted to many of the later ironclads.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] Some of these, such as the British *Victoria* class, carried guns as large as 16.25 inches (413 mm) in diameter, while the Italian *Duilio*-class ironclads were armed with colossal 17.7-inch (450 mm) guns.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] In the 1880s, opposition to fleets of large, expensive ironclads arose around the world, but most notably in France, where a group of naval officers led by Admiral Théophile Aube formed the *Jeune École* (Young School).
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] The theory, which held as one of its core tenets that small, cheap torpedo boats could easily defeat ironclads, was based on combat experience during the Russo-Turkish War of 1877–1878.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] The doctrine also posited that modern steel-hulled cruisers could defeat a more powerful navy by attacking the country's merchant shipping, rather than engage in a direct battle.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] The concept proved to be highly influential for several years, shaping the construction programs of France, Germany, Italy, and Austria-Hungary, among others throughout the world.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] In 1889, the British government passed the Naval Defence Act 1889, which embarked on a major naval construction program aimed at establishing the so-called two-power standard, whereby the Royal Navy would be stronger than the next two largest navies combined.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] The plan saw the construction of the eight *Royal Sovereign*-class battleships, which have been regarded as the first class of battleship that would retrospectively be referred to as "pre-dreadnought battleships".
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] These large battleships incorporated a number of major improvements over earlier vessels like the *Devastation*s, including a high freeboard for true ocean-going capability, more extensive armor protection, heavier secondary battery guns, and greater speed.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] The ships were armed with four 13.5 in (340 mm) guns in two twin mounts, fore and aft, which established the pattern for subsequent battleships.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] After building a trio of smaller second class battleships intended for the colonial empire, Britain followed with the nine-strong *Majestic*-class battleships in 1893–1895, which improved on the basic *Royal Sovereign* design.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] These ships adopted the 12 in (305 mm) gun, which would become the standard for all subsequent British pre-dreadnoughts.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] Foreign navies quickly began pre-dreadnoughts of their own; France began *Brennus* in 1889 and Germany laid down four *Brandenburg*-class battleships in 1890.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] The United States Navy laid down three *Indiana*-class battleships in 1891, the same year work began on the Russian battleship *Tri Sviatitelia*.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] Japan ordered the two *Fuji*-class battleships from British yards, to an improved *Royal Sovereign* design, in 1894.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] The Austro-Hungarian Navy eventually ordered its own pre-dreadnoughts, beginning with the *Habsburg* class in 1899.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] All of these ships carried guns of between 11 and 13.4 in (280 and 340 mm), save the Austro-Hungarian vessels, which, being significantly smaller than the rest, only carried 9.4 in (240 mm) guns.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] They also generally carried a light armament for defense against torpedo boats and other light craft.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] Some ships varied from this general pattern, such as the American *Indiana*s, which carried a heavier secondary battery of 8-inch (203 mm) guns, and the German *Brandenburg*s, which had six 11-inch guns for instead of the usual four heavy guns.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] Many of the early French pre-dreadnoughts, such as *Charles Martel*, carried a mixed heavy armament of two 12-inch and two 10.8-inch (274 mm) guns.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] Pre-dreadnoughts continued the technical innovations of the ironclad throughout the 1890s and early 1900s.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] Compound armor gave way to much stronger Harvey armor developed in the United States in 1890, which was in turn superseded by the German Krupp armor in 1894.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] As armor became stronger, it could be reduced in thickness considerably, which saved weight that could be allocated to other aspects of the ship design, and generally permitted larger and more capable battleships.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] At the same time, the advent of smokeless powder continued the trend begun in the French navy of comparatively smaller guns firing at higher velocities.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] Early on in the pre-dreadnought era, most navies standardized on the 12-inch gun; only Germany remained the significant outlier, relying on 11-inch and even 9.4-inch guns for its pre-dreadnoughts.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] Similarly, later in the pre-dreadnought era, the secondary batteries grew in caliber, usually to 7 to 8 in (178 to 203 mm) guns.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] In the last years of the 19th century and the first years of the 20th, the escalation in the building of battleships became an arms race between Britain and Germany.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] The German naval laws of 1890 and 1898 authorized a fleet of 38 battleships, a vital threat to the balance of naval power.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] Britain answered with further shipbuilding, but by the end of the pre-dreadnought era, British supremacy at sea had markedly weakened.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] In 1883, the United Kingdom had 38 ironclad battleships, twice as many as France and almost as many as the rest of the world put together.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] In 1897, Britain's lead was far smaller due to competition from France, Germany, and Russia, as well as the development of pre-dreadnought fleets in Italy, the United States and Japan.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] The Ottoman Empire, Spain, Sweden, Denmark, Norway, the Netherlands, Chile, and Brazil all had second-rate fleets led by armored cruisers, coastal defence ships or monitors.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] Pre-dreadnought battleships received their first test in combat in the Spanish–American War in 1898 at the Battle of Santiago de Cuba.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] An American squadron that included four pre-dreadnoughts had blockaded a Spanish squadron of four armored cruisers in Santiago de Cuba until 3 July, when the Spanish ships attempted to break through and escape.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] All four cruisers were destroyed in the ensuing engagement, as were a pair of Spanish destroyers, and the American ships received little damage in return.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] The battle seemed to indicate that the mixed batteries of pre-dreadnought battleships were very effective, as the medium-caliber guns had inflicted most of the damage (which reinforced the observations of the Battle of Manila Bay, where only cruisers armed with medium guns had been present).
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] It also led navies around the world to begin working on better solutions for rangefinding in the hope of improving gunnery at longer ranges.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] Conflicting colonial ambitions in Korea and Manchuria led Russia and Japan to the next major use of pre-dreadnoughts in combat.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] During the Russo-Japanese War of 1904–1905, squadrons of battleships engaged in a number of battles, including the Battle of the Yellow Sea and the Battle of Tsushima.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] Naval mines also proved to be a deadly threat to battleships on both sides, sinking the Russian *Petropavlovsk* in March 1904 and the Japanese battleships *Hatsuse* and *Yashima* on the same day in May.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] The action in the Yellow Sea began during a Russian attempt to break out of Port Arthur, which the Japanese under Admiral Tōgō Heihachirō had blockaded.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] The Russians outmaneuvered the Japanese and briefly escaped, but the latter's superior speed allowed them to catch up.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] A 12-inch shell struck the Russian flagship, killing the squadron commander and causing the Russian ships to fall into disarray and retreat back to Port Arthur.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] With night falling, the Japanese broke off and reimposed the blockade.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] At Tsushima, Togo outmaneuvered the Russian Second Pacific Squadron that had been sent to reinforce the Pacific Fleet, and the Japanese battleships quickly inflicted fatal damage with long-range fire from their 12-inch guns.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] In both actions during the Russo-Japanese War, the fleets engaged at longer range (as far as 12,000 yd (11,000 m) at the Yellow Sea), where only their 12-inch guns were effective.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] Only in the final stages of the battle at Tsushima, by which time the Russian fleet had been severely damaged and most of its modern battleships sunk or disabled, did the Japanese fleet close to effective range of their secondary guns, fighting as close as 2,700 yd (2,500 m).
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] The actions, particularly the decisive engagement at Tsushima, demonstrated that the lessons taken from the Spanish–American War were incorrect, and that the large-caliber gun should be the only offensive weapon carried by battleships.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] In the early 1900s, some naval theorists had begun to argue for future battleships to discard the heavy secondary batteries and instead carry only big guns.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] The first prominent example was Vittorio Cuniberti, the chief engineer of the Italian *Regia Marina* (Royal Navy); he published an article in 1903 titled "An Ideal Battleship for the British Navy" in *Jane's Fighting Ships*.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] The Japanese Navy was the first to actually order any of these new ships, beginning with the two *Satsuma*-class battleships in 1904, though due to shortages of 12-inch guns, they were completed with a mix of 12- and 10-inch (254 mm) guns.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] By early 1905, Fisher had converted to the 12-inch gun for his proposed new capital ships, and in March that year, the German Navy had decided to build an all-big-gun battleship for the planned *Nassau* class.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] The American *South Carolina* class was authorized in 1905, but work did not begin until December 1906.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] Though several navies had begun design work on all-big-gun battleships, the first to be completed was the British *Dreadnought*, which had been ordered by Fisher.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] He actually preferred a very large armored cruiser equipped with an all-big-gun armament, which would come to be known as the battlecruiser, and he only included *Dreadnought* in his 1905 construction program to appease naval officers who favored continued battleship building.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] Fisher believed that Britain's security against the French and Russian threats would be better guaranteed by squadrons of fast battlecruisers, three of which were laid down in 1906.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] Regardless of Fisher's intentions, the rapidly changing strategic calculus invalidated his plans and ensured that when the 1906–1907 program was being debated, Germany would be Britain's primary rival, the Royal Navy chose to build three more dreadnoughts instead of further battlecruisers.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] Reactions from the other naval powers was immediate; very few pre-dreadnoughts were built afterward, and in the first seven years of the ensuing arms race, all of the major naval powers either had their own dreadnoughts in service or nearing completion.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] Of these competitions, the Anglo-German race was the most significant, though others took place, such as the South American contest.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] Even naval powers of the second and third rank, such as Spain; Brazil, Chile, and Argentina in South America; and Greece and the Ottoman Empire in the Mediterranean had begun dreadnought programs, either domestically or ordering abroad.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] Technological development continued over the decade that followed *Dreadnought*'s launch.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] Already by 1910, the British had begun the first of the so-called "super-dreadnoughts" that carried significantly more powerful 13.5-inch (340 mm) guns, all on the centerline.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] The United States followed suit in 1911, though increasing the caliber of their guns to 14 inches (356 mm).
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] France adopted a 13.4 in (340 mm) gun for its *Bretagne*-class battleships, laid down in 1912.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] That year, Japan laid down the first of its *Fusō*-class battleships, also armed with a 14-inch main battery.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] The Germans waited until 1913, but skipped directly to 15-inch (381 mm) guns.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] By this time, Britain had led the way to the 15-inch gun with the *Queen Elizabeth* class begun in late 1912.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] But more importantly than the increase of caliber, the *Queen Elizabeth*s were the first completely oil-fired battleships and the first fast battleships.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] At around the same time, the United States introduced the next major innovation in battleship design: the all or nothing armor system in the *Nevada* class laid down in 1912.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] The heaviest possible armor was used to protect the ship's propulsion machinery and ammunition magazines, but intermediate protection was stripped away from non-essential areas, since this mid-weight armor only served to detonate armor-piercing shells.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] By the start of World War I in July 1914, the Royal Navy's Grand Fleet outnumbered the German High Seas Fleet by 21 to 13 in numbers of dreadnought battleships and 4 to 3 in battlecruisers.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] And over the course of the war, Britain would add another 14 dreadnoughts, while Germany completed another 6.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] German strategy presumed that Britain would launch an immediate offensive into the southern North Sea, but the British preferred to establish a distant blockade, which very quickly stopped German maritime trade.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] Both sides were aware that, because of the greater number of British dreadnoughts, a full fleet engagement would be likely to result in a British victory.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] The German strategy was therefore to try to provoke an engagement on their terms: either to induce a part of the Grand Fleet to enter battle alone, or to fight a pitched battle near the German coastline, where friendly minefields, torpedo-boats and submarines could be used to even the odds.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] The British fleet commander, Admiral John Jellicoe, refused to be drawn into unfavorable conditions and enforced the blockade at the English Channel and between Scotland and Norway.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] In the Baltic Sea, Germany found itself in the reverse situation, in an even more lopsided fashion versus its Russian opponent.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] The Russian Baltic Fleet had only four dreadnoughts at the start of the war, so they adopted a purely defensive approach to guard the capital at Petrograd and the northern flank of the Russian army units fighting on the Eastern Front.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] In the Mediterranean Sea, Italy initially remained neutral, despite being a member of the Triple Alliance with Germany and Austria-Hungary, leaving the latter to face the French Navy and British Mediterranean Fleet alone.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] After ensuring the French army units in French North Africa were safely convoyed to France, the French fleet sailed to the Adriatic Sea to blockade the Austro-Hungarian fleet, which refused to leave their fortified bases.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] The French, like the other major European naval commanders, had failed to consider that their opponents would not concede to engaging in battle on terms unfavorable to them.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] The Adriatic quickly turned into another stalemate as the threat of Austro-Hungarian mines and submarines prevented a more aggressive employment of the French fleet.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] The Germans embarked on a number of sweeps into the North Sea and raids on British coastal towns to draw out part of the Grand Fleet, which would be isolated and destroyed.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] These included the raid on Scarborough, Hartlepool and Whitby, where the Germans nearly caught an isolated British battle squadron, but turned away, thinking that it was the entire Grand Fleet.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] This strategy ultimately led to the Battle of Jutland on 31 May – 1 June 1916, the largest clash of battleship fleets.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] The first stage of the battle was fought largely by the two sides' battlecruiser squadrons, though the British were supported by four of the *Queen Elizabeth*-class battleships.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] After both battleship fleets engaged, the British crossed the Germans' "T" twice, but the latter managed to extricate themselves from the action as darkness fell.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] Early on 1 June, the High Seas Fleet had reached port.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] In the course of the fighting, three British battlecruisers were destroyed, as was one German battlecruiser and the old pre-dreadnought *Pommern*.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] Numerous cruisers and destroyers were lost on both sides as well.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] The Germans made two further offensive operations in the months after Jutland.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] The first, which led to the inconclusive action of 19 August, saw one German battleship torpedoed by a British submarine and two British cruisers sunk by German U-boats.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] This incident convinced the British that the risks posed by submarines were too great to send the Grand Fleet into the southern North Sea, barring exceptional circumstances like a German invasion of Britain.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] In the second German operation, which took place on 18–19 October, a German cruiser was damaged by a submarine and the Grand Fleet remained in port.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] By this time, the Germans were similarly convinced of the futility of their attempts to isolate part of the British fleet, and discontinued such raids.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] They instead turned to unrestricted submarine warfare, which resulted in their battleships being reduced to a supporting force that guarded the U-boat bases.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] In the Baltic, the Germans made two attempts to capture the islands in the Gulf of Riga.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] The first came in August 1915, and in the ensuing Battle of the Gulf of Riga, a pair of German dreadnoughts engaged in an artillery duel at long range with the Russian pre-dreadnought *Slava* guarding the minefields that protected the gulf.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] The Germans drove off the Russian ship, cleared the minefield, but by the time they entered the gulf, submarines had reportedly arrived.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] Unwilling to risk the battleships in the shallow, confined waters of the gulf, the Germans retreated.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] The second attempt—Operation Albion—took place in October 1917.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] During the Battle of Moon Sound, another pair of German dreadnoughts damaged *Slava* so badly that she had to be scuttled, and the Germans completed their amphibious assault on the islands.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] The modern units of the French and British fleets in the Mediterranean spent much of the war guarding the entrance to the Adriatic, first based at Malta and later moving to Corfu.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] They saw very little action through the war.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] For their part, the Italians were content to reinforce the blockading force guarding the Adriatic, as they, too, were unwilling to risk their capital ships in the mine and submarine infested waters of the Austrian Littoral.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] Instead, light forces carried out most of the operations.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] Meanwhile, several French and British pre-dreadnoughts were sent to attack the Ottoman defenses guarding the Dardanelles.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] In the ensuing naval operations from February to March 1915, several battleships were sunk or damaged by mines and torpedoes.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] When the fleets failed to break through the defenses, the British and French decided to land at Gallipoli to try to take the fortifications by land; the remaining battleships were thereafter used to provide naval gunfire support.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] This, too, ultimately failed and by January 1916, the British and French withdrew their troops.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] Russian battleships saw more action in the Black Sea against their Ottoman opponents.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] By 1916, the Russians had completed a pair of dreadnoughts in the Black Sea, which severely curtailed Ottoman freedom of maneuver.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] In the course of the war, older pre-dreadnoughts proved to be highly vulnerable to underwater damage, whether by naval mine or ship-launched or submarine-delivered torpedoes.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] HMS *Formidable* was sunk by a German U-boat in the English Channel in 1915.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] At the Dardanelles, HMS *Majestic* was sunk by a German U-boat, HMS *Goliath* was sunk by the Ottoman destroyer *Muavenet-i Milliye*.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] The British *Ocean* and *Irresistible* and the French *Bouvet* were all sunk by mines.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] HMS *Russell* and HMS *Cornwallis* were both sunk by mines in the Mediterranean in 1916 and 1917, respectively.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] HMS *King Edward VII* was similarly mined and sunk off the British coast in 1916, and HMS *Britannia* was sunk by a U-boat in the final days of the war.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] The French *Gaulois* and *Suffren* were sunk by U-boats in 1916, and *Danton* was torpedoed and sunk by a U-boat in 1917.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] At Jutland, the only battleship lost was the old pre-dreadnought *Pommern*, which was torpedoed by a destroyer.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] In contrast, dreadnoughts proved to be much more resilient to underwater attack.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] HMS *Marlborough* was damaged by a torpedo at Jutland, but nevertheless returned to port.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] The German SMS *Westfalen* was torpedoed at the action of 19 August 1916, and SMS *Grosser Kurfürst* and *Kronprinz* were torpedoed by the same submarine in November 1917; all three survived.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] SMS *Bayern* was mined during Operation Albion and remained in action against Russian artillery batteries for some time thereafter.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] Dreadnoughts lost to underwater attack were rare.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] HMS *Audacious* was sunk by a mine in October 1914, the Austro-Hungarian SMS *Szent Istvan* was sunk by Italian MAS boats in June 1918, and five months later, Italian frogmen sank *Viribus Unitis* using a powerful limpet mine.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] In the immediate aftermath of the war, the most modern units of the German fleet was interned at Scapa Flow, where in June 1919, their crews scuttled the fleet to avoid it being handed over to the Allies.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] The remaining dreadnoughts still in German ports were therefore seized as compensation for the scuttled ships.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] The postwar *Reichsmarine* of Weimar Germany was limited to a contingent of eight old pre-dreadnoughts (of which two would be kept in reserve) under the terms of the Treaty of Versailles; new battleships were subject to severe restrictions on size and armament.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] The surviving battleships of Austria-Hungary, the other defeated Central Power, were soon distributed among the Allies, to be broken up.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] While the other major naval powers remained free to build new battleships, most of them were financially crippled after the war.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] The prospect of a renewed naval arms race between the United States, United Kingdom, and Japan, appealed to few politicians in the three countries, and so they concluded the Washington Naval Treaty in 1922, which also included Italy and France.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] The treaty limited the number and size of battleships, and imposed a ten-year building holiday, along with other provisions.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] The treaty also imposed a ratio of 5:5:3 on total displacement of battleships for the US, UK, and Japan, respectively, and it severed the Anglo-Japanese Alliance.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] The only exceptions to the building holiday were for the two British *Nelson*-class battleships, which were permitted to give Britain parity with the latest American and Japanese battleships, which were all armed with 16-inch (406 mm) guns.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] The Washington treaty was followed by a series of other naval treaties, including the First London Naval Treaty (1930) and the Second London Naval Treaty (1936), which both set additional limits on major warships.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] The treaty limitations meant that fewer new battleships were launched in 1919–1939 than in 1905–1914.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] The treaties also inhibited development by imposing upper limits on the weights of ships.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] Designs like the projected British N3-class battleship, the first American *South Dakota* class, and the Japanese *Kii* class—all of which continued the trend to larger ships with bigger guns and thicker armor—never got off the drawing board.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] Those designs which were commissioned during this period were referred to as treaty battleships.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] The collapse of the treaty system began during the negotiations for the Second London Treaty, where Japan demanded parity with Britain and the US, which the latter two flatly rejected.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] Japan withdrew from the treaty system in 1936, though the agreements remained in effect until January 1937.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] As early as 1914, the British Admiral Percy Scott predicted that battleships would soon be made irrelevant by aircraft.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] Between 1916 and 1918, US Admiral William Fullam published a series of papers stating that aircraft would become an independent strike arm of the fleet, and argued that the *Lexington*-class battlecruisers then under construction should be converted to aircraft carriers than scrapped.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] By the end of World War I, aircraft had successfully adopted the torpedo as a weapon.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] In 1921 the Italian general and air theorist Giulio Douhet completed a hugely influential treatise on strategic bombing titled *The Command of the Air*, which foresaw the dominance of air power over conventional military and naval forces.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] In 1921, US General Billy Mitchell used the ex-German dreadnought SMS *Ostfriesland* in a series of bombing tests conducted by the Navy and Army.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] The test involved a series of attacks on the stationary, unmanned ships using low-level, land-based bombers dropping bombs that ranged from 550 to 2,000 pounds (250 to 910 kg).
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] *Ostfriesland* was sunk by the heaviest bombs, though Mitchell broke the rules of the tests and the subsequent report concluded that had the ship been crewed, underway, and firing back at the aircraft, damage control teams aboard *Ostfriesland* could have managed any damage inflicted.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] Mitchell and his supporters nevertheless embarked on a public campaign that falsely claimed that *Ostfriesland* was a super-battleship, and the quick sinking proved that battleships were obsolete.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] Mitchell would eventually be subjected to a court martial, convicted, and discharged from the Army over his insubordinate tactics.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] Naval aviation traces its origin back to the first decade of the 20th century, though early efforts were based on using aircraft to scout for the fleet and help direct gunfire at long range.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] A number of experimental aircraft carriers were employed during World War I, primarily by the Royal Navy, all converted from merchant vessels or existing warships.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] The US Navy completed its first carrier, USS *Langley*, in 1922.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] But aircraft carriers in the 1920s faced a number of challenges to be overcome: aircraft of the day were short-ranged, which meant the carrier had to be very close to the enemy to be able to launch and then recover a strike, which exposed the carriers to attack.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] In addition, the available planes had insufficient power to carry meaningful bomb loads.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] Early naval aviators nevertheless pioneered effective tactics like dive bombing during this period.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] Because the Washington Treaty system precluded the construction of any new battleships until the early 1930s, the major naval powers began a program of modernization for their most effective battleships.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] Britain conducted a series of refits to their *Queen Elizabeth*-class battleships through the 1920s, adding anti-torpedo bulges, additional anti-aircraft guns, and aircraft catapults; further refits in the 1930s increased armor protection and further strengthened their anti-aircraft batteries.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] The *Revenge*-class battleships were less heavily modified during the period.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] The US *Florida*, *Wyoming* class, and *New York* classes received similar treatments in the 1920s, while the *Nevada* and *Pennsylvania* classes received new turbines, additional armor, and more anti-aircraft guns.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] The Japanese similarly updated their *Fusō*, *Ise*, and *Nagato*-class battleships, and rebuilt three of the four *Kongō*-class battlecruisers into fast battleships, albeit with significantly inferior protection compared to the other ships.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] They all also received distinctive pagoda masts.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] *Hiei* was initially disarmed to serve as a training ship under the terms of the Washington Treaty, but was remilitarized in the late 1930s.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] In the 1930s, all four classes were lengthened and had their propulsion systems improved to increase their speeds.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] The French and Italian navies were exempted from the 10-year building holiday, owing to the comparative obsolescence of their battleships; they were permitted to build 70,000 long tons (71,000 t) worth of battleships.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] But the weak economies of both countries led both to defer new construction until Germany began building the *Deutschland* class of heavily armed cruiser at the end of the 1920s.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] This prompted the French to build the *Dunkerque* class of small, fast battleships armed with 13 in (330 mm) guns, which led to a short arms race in Europe in the mid-1930s.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] The Italians responded with the significantly larger and more powerful *Littorio* class, armed with 15-inch guns.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] The French, in turn, began the *Richelieu*-class battleships to counter the *Littorio*s.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] By this time, Nazi Germany had signed the Anglo-German Naval Agreement in 1935, which removed the restrictions imposed by Versailles and pegged German naval strength to 35% of British tonnage.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] This permitted the construction of two *Scharnhorst*-class battleships, which were also a response to the *Dunkerque*s.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] The advent of the *Richelieu*s prompted the Germans to build the two *Bismarck*-class battleships late in the decade.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] The Germans thereafter embarked on the ambitious Plan Z naval construction program, which included a total of eight battleships, of which the *Bismarck*s would be the first two.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] Against the backdrop of European rearmament in the mid-1930s, Britain began planning its first battleship class in a decade: the *King George V* class.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] These were armed with 14-inch guns intended to comply with the terms of the Second London Naval Conference, and they were laid down in 1937.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] The United States began their *North Carolina* class at the same time, and though they were intended to be armed with 14-inch guns, Japan's refusal to agree to the Second London Treaty led the US to invoke a clause of the treaty that allowed an increase to 16-inch guns.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] In 1939, these were followed by the four *South Dakota*-class battleships, and in 1940 by the first of four *Iowa*-class battleships.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p01] For its part, Japan had decided to embark on a program of four very large *Yamato*-class battleships, armed with 18-inch (457 mm) guns, as early as 1934, though work did not begin on the first ship until late 1937.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p02] The German pre-dreadnought *Schleswig-Holstein* fired the first shots of World War II by initiating the bombardment of the Polish garrison at Westerplatte in the early hours on 1 September 1939.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p02] The German *Scharnhorst*-class battleships caught the British carrier HMS *Glorious* off the coast of Norway and sank her during the Norwegian campaign.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p02] In the former action, the British sank a pair of older *Bretagne*-class battleships and the fast battleship *Dunkerque*, though the latter was refloated and repaired.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p02] At Dakar, the French battleship *Richelieu* and other forces fended off the British task force, which resulted in the torpedoing of the battleship HMS *Resolution*, which was severely damaged.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p02] Italy entered the war in June 1940, shortly before the French defeat.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p02] In November, the British launched a nighttime airstrike on the naval base at Taranto; in the Battle of Taranto, Fairey Swordfish torpedo bombers disabled three Italian battleships, though they were subsequently repaired.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p02] Over the next year, Italian and British battleships engaged in a number of inconclusive actions as they contested the supply lines to North Africa.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p02] These included the Battle of Cape Spartivento in November 1940 and the Battle of Cape Matapan in March 1941.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p02] At Matapan, the battleship *Vittorio Veneto* was badly damaged by a Swordfish, though the ship returned to port.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p02] The British battleships *Valiant*, *Warspite*, and *Barham* nevertheless caught a group of three heavy cruisers that evening and destroyed them in a furious, close-range night action.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p02] Convoy battles continued through 1941 and into 1942, with actions such as First and Second Sirte.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p02] By 1943, Italian operations were sharply reduced due to a shortage of fuel, and after the Allied invasion of Italy, the country surrendered, allowing most of its fleet to be interned at Malta.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p02] While on the way, the battleship *Roma* was sunk by a German Fritz X guided glide bomb.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p02] In the meantime, in January 1941, the Germans began to send their few battleships on commerce raiding operations in the Atlantic, starting with the two *Scharnhorst*-class ships in Operation Berlin, which was not particularly successful.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p02] *Bismarck* followed with Operation Rheinübung in May, which resulted in two actions, the Battle of the Denmark Strait and the sinking of *Bismarck*.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p02] During the operation, *Bismarck* was crippled by Swordfish torpedo bombers, which allowed a pair of British battleships to catch and destroy her.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p02] By 1942, the last operational German battleships—*Tirpitz* and *Scharnhorst*—were sent to occupied Norway to serve as a fleet in being to tie down British naval resources and to attack supply convoys to the Soviet Union.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p02] The battleship HMS *Duke of York* eventually sank *Scharnhorst* at the Battle of North Cape in December 1943, and *Tirpitz* was destroyed by British heavy bombers in 1944.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p02] On 7 December 1941, the Japanese launched a surprise attack on the US naval base at Pearl Harbor.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p02] Over the course of two waves of dive-, level- and torpedo bombers, the Japanese sank or destroyed five battleships and inflicted serious damage to the facilities there.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p02] Three days later, land-based Japanese aircraft operating out of French Indochina, then occupied by Japan, caught and sank the British battleship HMS *Prince of Wales* and the battlecruiser HMS *Repulse* off the coast of British Malaya.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p02] Though the Taranto and Pearl Harbor strikes were significant steps toward aircraft replacing the battleship as the primary naval striking arm, the sinking of *Prince of Wales* and *Repulse* marked the first time aircraft had sunk capital ships that were maneuvering and returning fire.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p02] Employment of battleships during the Pacific War was limited by a number of factors.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p02] Japanese strategic doctrine, the *Kantai Kessen*, envisioned a decisive clash of battleships at the end of the war, and so kept most of their battleships in home waters, and only the four *Kongō*s were routinely detached to escort the aircraft carriers of the *Kido Butai*.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p02] For their part, the US kept its surviving pre-war battleships out of action primarily because they were too slow to keep up with the carriers.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p02] Later in the war, they were employed as coastal bombardment vessels.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p02] Nevertheless, American and Japanese battleships saw significant action during the Guadalcanal campaign in 1942, most notably at the Naval Battle of Guadalcanal in November.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p02] There, an American squadron centered on the battleships *Washington* and *South Dakota* intercepted and sank the battleship *Kirishima*, though *South Dakota* received significant damage in return.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p02] As more and more of the American fast battleships entered service from 1942, onward, they were frequently used as escorts for the fast carrier task force that was the US Navy's primary striking arm in its campaign across the central Pacific.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p02] During the Philippines campaign, battleships played a central role during the Battle of Leyte Gulf in October 1944.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p02] The action was one of the largest naval battles in history, which took place over several days and as three Japanese fleets attacked the Allied invasion fleet.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p02] The Japanese battleship *Musashi*, part of Center Force, was sunk by American carrier aircraft during the Battle of Sibuyan Sea on 24 October.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p02] During the Battle of Surigao Strait the following night, several US battleships that had been repaired from the attack on Pearl Harbor defeated the Japanese Southern Force that included a pair of battleships.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p02] Center Force attacked again on 25 October in the Battle off Samar, but was driven off by destroyers and aircraft from several escort carriers.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p02] During the Battle of Okinawa in April 1945, Japan sent *Yamato* as a final suicide mission to attack the landing beaches and attempt to stop the invasion of the island.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p02] American aircraft scored between nine and thirteen torpedo hits and six bomb hits on the ship and sank her.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p02] *Haruna* was sunk by US aircraft off Kure, Japan, in July.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p02] The war ended with the Japanese surrender aboard the battleship USS *Missouri* in September 1945.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p02] After World War II, several navies retained their existing battleships, but most were either placed in their reserve fleets or scrapped outright.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p02] Of their surviving pre-war battleships, most of the American vessels were either scrapped or sunk as target ships by 1948, though the most modern vessels, those of the *Tennessee* and *Maryland* classes, survived until the late 1950s and early 1960s.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p02] One of the earlier vessels, USS *Texas*, was preserved as a museum ship.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p02] The four *King George V*-class ships were all broken up by 1957, Only two battleships—the British HMS *Vanguard* and the French *Jean Bart*—were completed after the war.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p02] *Vanguard* did not long outlast the *King George V*s, being scrapped herself in 1960.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p02] *Jean Bart* (and her sister *Richelieu*) remained in the French fleet's inventory until the early 1960s, when they were discarded.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p02] Three of the six American *North Carolina*- and *South Dakota*-class ships were similarly scrapped in the early 1960s, but the other three—*North Carolina*, *Massachusetts*, and *Alabama*—were retained as museum ships.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p02] With the reduced naval budgets of the immediate postwar period, the US Navy chose to concentrate its resources on its carrier force.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p02] Besides the rise of aircraft carriers as the preeminent naval striking force, the advent of nuclear weapons influenced the decision to abandon large battleship fleets.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p02] In 1946, *Nagato*, which was seized by the US, and four American battleships were used during the Operation Crossroads nuclear weapons tests, though three of the American ships survived the two blasts and were later sunk with conventional weapons.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p02] Of the remaining, smaller battleships fleets, Italy retained its two *Andrea Doria*-class battleships, of 1913 vintage, until the late 1950s and early 1960s, when they were scrapped.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p02] One other battleship, *Giulio Cesare* was taken by the Soviets as reparations and renamed *Novorossiysk*; she was sunk by a mine in the Black Sea on 29 October 1955.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p02] The two surviving *Littorio*-class ships were taken by the US and UK as war reparations and scrapped in the late 1940s.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p02] The Soviets still had a pair of World War I-era battleships—*Parizhskaya Kommuna* and *Gangut*—but they, too, were scrapped in the late 1950s.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p02] The three large South American navies still had a handful of pre-World War I dreadnoughts in service after the war.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p02] Brazil eventually discarded its two *Minas Gerais*-class battleships in the early 1950s; *Argentina* sold its two *Rivadavia*-class battleships in 1956; the last ship in the region, the Chilean *Almirante Latorre*, followed them to the breakers' yard in 1959.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p02] The four *Iowa*-class battleships were the only vessels of the type to see significant combat after World War II.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p02] All four ships were reactivated for gunfire support duties during the Korean War in the early 1950s, and *New Jersey* was also deployed during the Vietnam War in 1968–1969 for the same task.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p02] All four ships were modernized in the early 1980s with Tomahawk cruise missiles, Harpoon anti-ship missiles, and Phalanx CIWS systems, along with the latest radar systems.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p02] They were recommissioned as part of the 600-ship Navy program under President Ronald Reagan.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p02] *New Jersey* next saw action in 1982, bombarding Syrian artillery during the Lebanese Civil War.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p02] *Missouri* and *Wisconsin* took part in Operation Desert Storm against Iraqi forces in 1991, bombarding enemy positions along the coast.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p02] The ships proved to be expensive to operate, and they required thousands of men to keep in service, so *Iowa* and *New Jersey* were already back in reserve by that time, and *Missouri* and *Wisconsin* were also decommissioned by the end of 1991.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p02] All four were struck from the Naval Vessel Register in 1995.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p02] When the last *Iowa*-class ship was finally stricken from the Naval Vessel Registry, no battleships remained in service or in reserve with any navy worldwide.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p02] A number are preserved as museum ships, either afloat or in drydock.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p02] The U.S. has eight battleships on display: *Massachusetts*, *North Carolina*, *Alabama*, *Iowa*, *New Jersey*, *Missouri*, *Wisconsin*, and *Texas*.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p02] *Missouri* and *New Jersey* are museums at Pearl Harbor and Camden, New Jersey, respectively.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p02] *Iowa* is on display as an educational attraction at the Los Angeles Waterfront in San Pedro, California.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p02] *Wisconsin* now serves as a museum ship in Norfolk, Virginia.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p02] *Massachusetts*, which has the distinction of never having lost a man during service, is on display at the Battleship Cove naval museum in Fall River, Massachusetts.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p02] *Texas*, the first battleship turned into a museum, is normally on display at the San Jacinto Battleground State Historic Site, near Houston, but as of 2021 is closed for repairs.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p02] *North Carolina* is on display in Wilmington, North Carolina.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p02] *Alabama* is on display in Mobile, Alabama.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p02] The USS Arizona Memorial was erected over the wreck of *Arizona*, which was sunk during the Pearl Harbor attack in 1941, to commemorate those killed in the raid.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p02] Memorials were also placed to mark the wreck of *Utah*, also sunk during the attack.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p02] The only other 20th-century battleship on display is the Japanese pre-dreadnought *Mikasa*, preserved since 1923.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p02] On 22 December 2025, the United States Navy announced the planned construction of new battleships.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p02] The Trump class will be the first nuclear-powered battleship, and it is planned to carry nuclear-capable cruise missiles, and conventional weapons.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p02] For much of their existence, battleships were the embodiment of sea power.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p02] The American naval officer Alfred Thayer Mahan argued in his seminal 1890 work, *The Influence of Sea Power upon History*, a strong navy was vital to the success of a nation, and control of the seas was a prerequisite for the projection of force.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p02] Conversely, countries with weak navies would inevitably decline.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p02] Mahan argued that the cruiser warfare advocated by the *Jeune Ecole* could never be decisive, and that only fleets of battleships could control sea lanes and enforce blockades of an enemy's coast.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p02] The book proved to be widely influential across the world's navies; it was translated into German in 1896, where it was used to support the German naval expansion program championed by Alfred von Tirpitz.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p02] A Japanese-language translation also appeared in 1896, and it soon became required reading at the Japanese naval academy.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p02] By the end of the decade, Russian, French, Italian, and Spanish versions were produced.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p02] The "fleet in being" in part acts as a deterrent against attack.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p02] The concept underpinned Tirpitz's so-called "risk theory" that was the basis of his program to build a German battle fleet.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p02] Even if the Royal Navy maintained a numerical superiority, the risk that the German fleet would inflict grievous damage even in the case of a British victory would militate against any such battle taking place, and Germany would be free to pursue its global ambitions.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p02] By the 1890s, naval tacticians had developed a number of formations in which to employ battleships.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p02] The most prominent were referred to as "line ahead" and "line abreast".
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p02] The former, the standard tactic during the age of sail, arrayed ships in a single-file line, which emphasized broadside fire.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p02] The latter placed ships side-by-side, which was suited to close-range melees where ramming and torpedoes could be effectively employed; after Tegetthoff's success at Lissa in 1866 used a modified line abreast formation, the tactic enjoyed a period of popularity for several years.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p02] By the 1880s, line-ahead tactics had returned to prominence.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p02] Royal Navy officers devised the tactic referred to as "crossing the T" of an enemy fleet, whereby one fleet steaming in line-ahead formation crossed in front of another line of battleships.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p02] This maneuver would allow one's own battleships to concentrate entire broadsides on the leading enemy ship, while one's opponent could only reply with their forward guns.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p02] Many navies adopted the tactic soon thereafter.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p02] As the threat of underwater attack, including mines and torpedoes, developed after the 1860s, capital ships could no longer maintain close blockades of enemy ports.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p02] This required smaller, faster scouts to observe hostile ports so that an enemy fleet could be brought to battle.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p02] Modern cruisers began to be built in the 1880s for this purpose.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p02] Almost immediately after the invention of the airplane, navies recognized its potential as a reconnaissance unit for the fleet's battleships.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p02] The Austro-Hungarian Navy, then following the *Jeune École* doctrine of the 1870s and 1880s, devised the tactic of placing torpedo boats alongside battleships; these would hide behind the larger ships until gun-smoke obscured visibility enough for them to dart out and fire their torpedoes.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p02] While this tactic was made less effective by the development of smokeless propellant, the threat from more capable torpedo craft (later including submarines) remained.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p02] By the 1890s, the Royal Navy had developed the first destroyers, which were initially designed to intercept and drive off any attacking torpedo boats.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p02] The other major naval powers quickly followed suit with similar vessels of their own.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p02] The presence of battleships had a great psychological and diplomatic impact.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p02] Similar to possessing nuclear weapons in the second half of the 20th century, the ownership of battleships marked a country as a regional or global power, and the ability to build them domestically signified that a country could claim to be a great power.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p02] Even during the Cold War, the psychological impact of a battleship was significant.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p02] In September 1983, when Druze militia in Lebanon's Shouf Mountains fired upon U.S.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p02] Marine peacekeepers, the arrival of USS *New Jersey* stopped the firing.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p02] Gunfire from *New Jersey* later killed militia leaders.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p02] Battleships were the largest and most complex, and hence the most expensive warships of their time; as a result, the value of investment in battleships has always been contested.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p02] As the French politician Etienne Lamy wrote in 1879, "The construction of battleships is so costly, their effectiveness so uncertain and of such short duration, that the enterprise of creating an armored fleet seems to leave fruitless the perseverance of a people".
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p02] The *Jeune École* school of thought of the 1870s and 1880s sought alternatives to the crippling expense and debatable utility of a conventional battlefleet.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p02] It proposed what would nowadays be termed a sea denial strategy, based on fast, long-ranged cruisers for commerce raiding and torpedo boat flotillas to attack enemy ships attempting to blockade French ports.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p02] The ideas of the *Jeune École* were ahead of their time; it was not until the 20th century that efficient mines, torpedoes, submarines, and aircraft were available that allowed similar ideas to be effectively implemented.
[src:broadside-naval/battleship-p02] The determination of powers such as Germany to build battlefleets with which to confront much stronger rivals has been criticized by historians, who emphasize the futility of investment in a battlefleet that has no chance of matching its opponent in an actual battle.
[src:broadside-naval/broadside-naval] From the 16th century until the early decades of the steamship, vessels had rows of guns set in each side of the hull.
[src:broadside-naval/broadside-naval] Firing all guns on one side of the ship became known as a "broadside".
[src:broadside-naval/broadside-naval] The cannons of 18th-century men of war were accurate only at short range, and their penetrating power mediocre, which meant that the thick hulls of wooden ships could only be pierced at short ranges.
[src:broadside-naval/broadside-naval] These wooden ships sailed closer and closer towards each other until cannon fire would be effective.
[src:broadside-naval/broadside-naval] Each tried to be the first to fire a broadside, often giving one party a decisive headstart in the battle when it crippled the other ship.
[src:broadside-naval/broadside-naval] Since ancient times, war at sea had been fought much like on land: with melee weapons and bows and arrows, but on floating wooden platforms rather than battlefields.
[src:broadside-naval/broadside-naval] Though the introduction of firearms was a significant change, it only slowly changed the dynamics of ship-to-ship combat.
[src:broadside-naval/broadside-naval] The first guns on ships were small wrought-iron pieces mounted on the open decks and in the fighting tops, often requiring only one or two men to handle them.
[src:broadside-naval/broadside-naval] They were designed to injure, kill or simply stun, shock and frighten the enemy prior to boarding.
[src:broadside-naval/broadside-naval] As guns were made more durable to withstand stronger gunpowder charges, they increased their potential to inflict critical damage to the vessel rather than just its crew.
[src:broadside-naval/broadside-naval] Since these guns were much heavier than the earlier anti-personnel weapons, they had to be placed lower in the ships, and fire from gunports, to avoid ships becoming unstable.
[src:broadside-naval/broadside-naval] In Northern Europe the technique of building ships with clinker planking made it difficult to cut ports in the hull; clinker-built (or clench-built) ships had much of their structural strength in the outer hull.
[src:broadside-naval/broadside-naval] The solution was the gradual adoption of carvel-built ships that relied on an internal skeleton structure to bear the weight of the ship.
[src:broadside-naval/broadside-naval] The development of propulsion during the 15th century from single-masted, square-rigged cogs to three-masted carracks with a mix of square and lateen sails made ships nimbler and easier to maneuver.
[src:broadside-naval/broadside-naval] Gunports cut in the hull of ships were introduced, according to tradition, in 1501 by Breton shipwright called Descharges, but it is just as likely to have been a gradual adaptation of loading ports in the stern of merchant vessels that had already been in use for centuries.
[src:broadside-naval/broadside-naval] Initially, the gunports were used to mount heavy stern chasers pointing aft, but soon gun ports migrated to the sides of ships.
[src:broadside-naval/broadside-naval] This made possible coordinated volleys from all the guns on one side of a ship for the first time in history, at least in theory.
[src:broadside-naval/broadside-naval] Guns in the 16th century were considered to be in fixed positions and were intended to be fired independently rather than in concerted volleys.
[src:broadside-naval/broadside-naval] It was not until the 1590s that the word "broadside" in English was commonly used to refer to gunfire from the side of a ship rather than the ship's side itself.
[src:broadside-naval/broadside-naval] The main batteries in 20th century battleships tended to be powered gun turrets which could swivel 180 degrees or more to establish wider firing arcs around the entire vessel.
[src:broadside-naval/broadside-naval] Additionally, directing the guns to the port or starboard side projected the massive muzzle blast out over the ocean, while firing the guns too close to the deck could cause damage to the ship.
[src:broadside-naval/broadside-naval] When the term is used in this way, it can be calculated by multiplying the shell weight of the ship's main armament shells times the number of barrels that can be brought to bear.
[src:broadside-naval/broadside-naval] If some turrets are incapable of firing to either side of the vessel, only the maximum number of barrels which can fire to one side or the other are counted.
[src:broadside-naval/broadside-naval] For example, the American *Iowa*-class battleships carried a main armament of nine 16-inch (406 mm) main guns in turrets which could all be trained to a single broadside.
[src:broadside-naval/broadside-naval] Each 16-inch shell weighed 2,700 pounds (1,200 kg), which when multiplied by nine (the total number of barrels in all three turrets) equals a total of 24,300 pounds (11,022 kg).
[src:broadside-naval/broadside-naval] Thus, an *Iowa*-class battleship had a broadside of 12 short tons (11.0 tonnes), the weight of shells that she could theoretically land on a target in a single firing.
[src:broadside-naval/broadside-naval] See list of broadsides of major World War II ships for a comparison.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] A **cannon** (plural either *cannons* or *cannon*) is a large-caliber gun classified as a type of artillery, which usually launches a projectile using explosive chemical propellant.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] Gunpowder ("black powder") was the primary propellant before the invention of smokeless powder during the late 19th century.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] Cannons vary in gauge, effective range, mobility, rate of fire, angle of fire and firepower; different forms of cannon combine and balance these attributes in varying degrees, depending on their intended use on the battlefield.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] A cannon is a type of heavy artillery weapon.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] The word *cannon* is derived from several languages, in which the original definition can usually be translated as *tube*, *cane*, or *reed*.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] The earliest known depiction of cannons may have appeared in Song dynasty China as early as the 12th century; however, solid archaeological and documentary evidence of cannons do not appear until the 13th century.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] In 1288, Yuan dynasty troops are recorded to have used hand cannons in combat, and the earliest extant cannon bearing a date of production comes from the same period.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] By the end of the 14th century, cannons were widespread throughout Eurasia.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] Cannons were used primarily as anti-infantry weapons until around 1374, when large cannons were recorded to have breached walls for the first time in Europe.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] Cannons featured prominently as siege weapons.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] In 1464 a 16,000 kg (35,000 lb) cannon known as the Great Turkish Bombard was created in the Ottoman Empire.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] Cannons as field artillery became more important after 1453 when cannons broke down the walls of the Roman Empire's capital, with the introduction of limber, which greatly improved cannon maneuverability and mobility.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] European cannons reached their longer, lighter, more accurate, and more efficient "classic form" around 1480.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] This classic European cannon design stayed relatively consistent in form with minor changes until the 1750s.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] In the modern era, the term *cannon* has fallen into disuse, replaced by *guns* or *artillery*, if not a more specific term such as howitzer or mortar, except for automatic weapons called autocannons, usually firing explosive shells of larger caliber than machine-gun bullets.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] The word *cannon* is derived from the Old Italian word *cannone*, meaning "large tube", which came from the Latin *canna*, in turn originating from the Greek κάννα (*kanna*), "reed", and then generalised to mean any hollow tube-like object.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] The word has been used to refer to a gun since 1326 in Italy and 1418 in England.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] The plural forms *cannons* and *cannon* are both correct.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] The cannon may have appeared as early as the 12th century in China, and was probably a parallel development or evolution of the fire-lance, a short ranged anti-personnel weapon combining a gunpowder-filled tube and a polearm.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] Projectiles such as iron scraps or porcelain shards, mixed together with the gunpowder ("co-viative"), were placed in fire lance barrels at some point, and eventually, the paper and bamboo materials of fire lance barrels were replaced by metal.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] The earliest known depiction of a cannon is a sculpture from the Dazu Rock Carvings in Sichuan dated to 1128, however, the earliest archaeological samples and textual accounts do not appear until the 13th century.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] The primary extant specimens of cannon from the 13th century are the Wuwei Bronze Cannon dated to 1227, the Heilongjiang hand cannon dated to 1288, and the Xanadu Gun dated to 1298.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] However, only the Xanadu gun contains an inscription bearing a date of production, so it is considered the earliest confirmed extant cannon.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] The Xanadu Gun is 34.7 cm (13.7 in) in length and weighs 6.2 kg (14 lb).
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] The other cannons are dated using contextual evidence.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] The Heilongjiang hand cannon is also often considered by some to be the oldest firearm since it was unearthed near the area where the *History of Yuan* reports a battle took place involving hand cannons.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] According to the *History of Yuan*, in 1288, a Jurchen commander by the name of Li Ting led troops armed with hand cannons into battle against the rebel prince Nayan.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] Chen Bingying argues there were no guns before 1259, while Dang Shoushan believes the Wuwei gun and other Western Xia era samples point to the appearance of guns by 1220, and Stephen Haw goes even further by stating that guns were developed as early as 1200.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] Sinologist Joseph Needham and renaissance siege expert Thomas Arnold provide a more conservative estimate of around 1280 for the appearance of the "true" cannon.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] Whether or not any of these are correct, it seems likely that the gun was born sometime during the 13th century.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] References to cannons proliferated throughout China in the following centuries.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] In 1341 Xian Zhang wrote a poem called *The Iron Cannon Affair* describing a cannonball fired from an eruptor which could "pierce the heart or belly when striking a man or horse, and even transfix several persons at once." By the 1350s the cannon was used extensively in Chinese warfare.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] In 1358 the Ming army failed to take a city due to its garrisons' usage of cannon, however, they themselves would use cannon, in the thousands, later on during the siege of Suzhou in 1366.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] The Mongol invasion of Java in 1293 brought gunpowder technology to the Nusantara archipelago in the form of cannon (Chinese: *Pao*).
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] During the Ming dynasty cannons were used in riverine warfare at the Battle of Lake Poyang.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] One shipwreck in Shandong had a cannon dated to 1377 and an anchor dated to 1372.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] From the 13th to 15th centuries cannon-armed Chinese ships also travelled throughout Southeast Asia.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] Cannon appeared in Đại Việt by 1390 at the latest.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] The first of the western cannon to be introduced were breech-loaders in the early 16th century, which the Chinese began producing themselves by 1523 and improved on by including composite metal construction in their making.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] Japan did not acquire cannon until 1510 when a monk brought one back from China, and did not produce any in appreciable numbers.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] During the 1593 siege of Pyongyang, 40,000 Ming troops deployed a variety of cannons against Japanese troops.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] Despite their defensive advantage and the use of arquebus by Japanese soldiers, the Japanese were at a severe disadvantage due to their lack of cannon.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] Throughout the Japanese invasions of Korea (1592–1598), the Ming–Joseon coalition used artillery widely in land and naval battles, including on the turtle ships of Yi Sun-sin.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] According to Ivan Petlin, the first Russian envoy to Beijing, in September 1619, the city was armed with large cannon with cannonballs weighing more than 30 kg (66 lb).
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] Outside of China, the earliest texts to mention gunpowder are Roger Bacon's *Opus Majus* (1267) and *Opus Tertium* in what has been interpreted as references to firecrackers.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] In the early 20th century, a British artillery officer proposed that another work tentatively attributed to Bacon, *Epistola de Secretis Operibus Artis et Naturae, et de Nullitate Magiae*, dated to 1247, contained an encrypted formula for gunpowder hidden in the text.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] These claims have been disputed by science historians.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] In any case, the formula itself is not useful for firearms or even firecrackers, burning slowly and producing mostly smoke.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] There is a record of a gun in Europe dating to 1322 that was discovered in the nineteenth century, but the artifact has since been lost.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] In the same year, another similar illustration showed a darker gun being set off by a group of knights, in another work of de Milemete's, *De secretis secretorum Aristotelis*.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] On 11 February of that same year, the Signoria of Florence appointed two officers to obtain *canones de mettallo* and ammunition for the town's defence.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] In the following year a document from the Turin area recorded a certain amount was paid "for the making of a certain instrument or device made by Friar Marcello for the projection of pellets of lead".
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] A reference from 1331 describes an attack mounted by two Germanic knights on Cividale del Friuli, using man-portable gunpowder weapons of some sort.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] The 1320s seem to have been the takeoff point for guns in Europe according to most modern military historians.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] Scholars suggest that the lack of gunpowder weapons in a well-travelled Venetian's catalogue for a new crusade in 1321 implies that guns were unknown in Europe up until this point, further solidifying the 1320 mark, however more evidence in this area may be forthcoming in the future.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] The oldest extant cannon in Europe is a small bronze example unearthed in Loshult, Scania in southern Sweden.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] It dates from the early-mid 14th century, and is currently in the Swedish History Museum in Stockholm.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] Early cannons in Europe often shot arrows and were known by an assortment of names such as *pot-de-fer*, *tonnoire*, *ribaldis*, and *büszenpyle*.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] The *ribaldis*, which shot large arrows and simplistic grapeshot, were first mentioned in the English Privy Wardrobe accounts during preparations for the Battle of Crécy, between 1345 and 1346.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] The Florentine Giovanni Villani recounts their destructiveness, indicating that by the end of the battle, "the whole plain was covered by men struck down by arrows and cannon balls".
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] Similar cannon were also used at the siege of Calais (1346–47), although it was not until the 1380s that the *ribaudekin* clearly became mounted on wheels.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] The Battle of Crécy which pitted the English against the French in 1346 featured the early use of cannon which helped the longbowmen repulse a large force of Genoese crossbowmen deployed by the French.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] The English originally intended to use the cannon against cavalry sent to attack their archers, thinking that the loud noises produced by their cannon would panic the advancing horses along with killing the knights atop them.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] Early cannons could also be used for more than simply killing men and scaring horses.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] English cannon were used defensively in 1346 during the siege of Breteuil to launch fire onto an advancing siege tower.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] In this way, cannons could be used to burn down siege equipment before it reached the fortifications.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] The use of cannons to shoot fire could also be used offensively as another battle involved the setting of a castle ablaze with similar methods.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] The particular incendiary used in these projectiles was most likely a gunpowder mixture.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] This is one area where early Chinese and European cannons share a similarity as both were possibly used to shoot fire.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] Early European cannons were rather small, dwarfed by the bombards, which would come later.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] In fact, it is possible that the cannons used at Crécy were capable of being moved rather quickly as there is an anonymous chronicle that notes the guns being used to attack the French camp, indicating that they would have been mobile enough to press the attack.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] These smaller cannons would eventually give way to larger, wall-breaching guns by the end of the 1300s.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] There is no clear consensus on when the cannon first appeared in the Islamic world, with dates ranging from 1260 to the mid-14th century.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] However, some scholars do not accept these early dates.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] While the date of its first appearance is not entirely clear, the general consensus among most historians is that there is no doubt the Mamluk forces were using cannon by 1342.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] Other accounts may have also mentioned the use of cannon in the early 14th century.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] An Arabic text dating to 1320–1350 describes a type of gunpowder weapon called a *midfa* which uses gunpowder to shoot projectiles out of a tube at the end of a stock.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] Some scholars consider this a hand cannon while others dispute this claim.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] The Nasrid army besieging Elche in 1331 made use of "iron pellets shot with fire".
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] According to historian Ahmad Y. al-Hassan, during the Battle of Ain Jalut in 1260, the Mamluks used cannon against the Mongols.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] He claims that this was "the first cannon in history" and used a gunpowder formula almost identical to the ideal composition for explosive gunpowder.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] He also argues that this was not known in China or Europe until much later.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] Al-Hassan further claims that the earliest textual evidence of cannon is from the Middle East, based on earlier originals which report hand-held cannons being used by the Mamluks at the Battle of Ain Jalut in 1260.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] Such an early date is not accepted by some historians, including David Ayalon, Iqtidar Alam Khan, Joseph Needham and Tonio Andrade.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] Khan argues that it was the Mongols who introduced gunpowder to the Islamic world, and believes cannon only reached Mamluk Egypt in the 1370s.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] Needham argued that the term *midfa*, dated to textual sources from 1342 to 1352, did not refer to true hand-guns or bombards, and that contemporary accounts of a metal-barrel cannon in the Islamic world did not occur until 1365.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] Similarly, Andrade dates the textual appearance of cannons in middle eastern sources to the 1360s.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] Gabor Ágoston and David Ayalon note that the Mamluks had certainly used siege cannons by 1342 or the 1360s, respectively, but earlier uses of cannons in the Islamic World are vague with a possible appearance in the Emirate of Granada by the 1320s and 1330s, though evidence is inconclusive.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] Ibn Khaldun reported the use of cannon as siege machines by the Marinid sultan Abu Yaqub Yusuf at the siege of Sijilmasa in 1274.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] The passage by Ibn Khaldun on the Marinid siege of Sijilmassa in 1274 occurs as follows: "[The Sultan] installed siege engines ... and gunpowder engines ..., which project small balls of iron.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] These balls are ejected from a chamber ... placed in front of a kindling fire of gunpowder; this happens by a strange property which attributes all actions to the power of the Creator." The source is not contemporary and was written a century later, around 1382.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] Needham believes Ibn Khaldun was speaking of fire lances rather than hand cannon.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] The Ottoman Empire made good use of cannon as siege artillery.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] Sixty-eight super-sized bombards were used by Mehmed the Conqueror to capture Constantinople in 1453.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] Jim Bradbury argues that Urban, a Hungarian cannon engineer, introduced this cannon from Central Europe to the Ottoman realm; according to Paul Hammer, however, it could have been introduced from other Islamic countries which had earlier used cannons.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] These cannons could fire heavy stone balls a mile, and the sound of their blast could reportedly be heard from a distance of 10 miles (16 km).
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] Shkodëran historian Marin Barleti discusses Turkish bombards at length in his book *De obsidione Scodrensi* (1504), describing the 1478–79 siege of Shkodra in which eleven bombards and two mortars were employed.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] The Ottomans also used cannon to control passage of ships through the Bosphorus strait.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] Ottoman cannons also proved effective at stopping crusaders at Varna in 1444 and Kosovo in 1448 despite the presence of European cannon in the former case.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] The similar Dardanelles Guns (for the location) were created by Munir Ali in 1464 and were still in use during the Anglo-Turkish War (1807–1809).
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] These were cast in bronze into two parts: the chase (the barrel) and the breech, which combined weighed 18.4 tonnes.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] The two parts were screwed together using levers to facilitate moving it.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] Fathullah Shirazi, a Persian inhabitant of India who worked for Akbar in the Mughal Empire, developed a volley gun in the 16th century.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] While there is evidence of cannons in Iran as early as 1405 they were not widespread.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] This changed following the increased use of firearms by Shah Ismail I, and the Iranian army used 500 cannons by the 1620s, probably captured from the Ottomans or acquired by allies in Europe.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] By 1443, Iranians were also making some of their own cannon, as Mir Khawand wrote of a 1200 kg metal piece being made by an Iranian *rikhtegar* which was most likely a cannon.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] Due to the difficulties of transporting cannon in mountainous terrain, their use was less common compared to their use in Europe.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] Documentary evidence of cannons in Russia does not appear until 1382 and they were used only in sieges, often by the defenders.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] It was not until 1475 when Ivan III established the first Russian cannon foundry in Moscow that they began to produce cannons natively.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] The earliest surviving cannon from Russia dates to 1485.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] Later on, large cannons were known as bombards, ranging from three to five feet in length and were used by Dubrovnik and Kotor in defence during the later 14th century.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] The first bombards were made of iron, but bronze became more prevalent as it was recognized as more stable and capable of propelling stones weighing as much as 45 kilograms (99 lb).
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] Around the same period, the Byzantine Empire began to accumulate its own cannon to face the Ottoman Empire, starting with medium-sized cannon 3 feet (0.91 m) long and of 10 in calibre.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] The earliest reliable recorded use of artillery in the region was against the Ottoman siege of Constantinople in 1396, forcing the Ottomans to withdraw.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] The Ottomans acquired their own cannon and laid siege to the Byzantine capital again in 1422.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] By 1453, the Ottomans used 68 Hungarian-made cannon for the 55-day bombardment of the walls of Constantinople, "hurling the pieces everywhere and killing those who happened to be nearby".
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] The largest of their cannons was the Great Turkish Bombard, which required an operating crew of 200 men and 70 oxen, and 10,000 men to transport it.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] Gunpowder made the formerly devastating Greek fire obsolete, and with the final fall of Constantinople—which was protected by what were once the strongest walls in Europe—on 29 May 1453, "it was the end of an era in more ways than one".
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] Cannons were introduced to the Javanese Majapahit Empire when Kublai Khan's Mongol-Chinese army under the leadership of Ike Mese sought to invade Java in 1293.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] *History of Yuan* mentioned that the Mongol used a weapon called *p'ao* against Daha forces.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] This weapon is interpreted differently by researchers, it may be a trebuchet that throws thunderclap bombs, firearms, cannons, or rockets.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] It is possible that the gunpowder weapons carried by the Mongol–Chinese troops amounted to more than one type.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] Thomas Stamford Raffles wrote in *The History of Java* that in 1247 saka (1325 AD), cannons were widely used in Java especially by the Majapahit.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] It is recorded that the small kingdoms in Java that sought the protection of Majapahit had to hand over their cannons to the Majapahit.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] Majapahit under *Mahapatih* (prime minister) Gajah Mada (in office 1331–1364) utilized gunpowder technology obtained from Yuan dynasty for use in naval fleet.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] Mongol-Chinese gunpowder technology of Yuan dynasty resulted in eastern-style cetbang which is similar to Chinese cannon.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] Swivel guns however, only developed in the archipelago because of the close maritime relations of the Nusantara archipelago with the territory of West India after 1460 AD, which brought new types of gunpowder weapons to the archipelago, likely through Arab intermediaries.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] This weapon seems to be cannon and gun of Ottoman tradition, for example the prangi, which is a breech-loading swivel gun.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] A new type of cetbang, called the western-style cetbang, was derived from the Turkish prangi.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] Just like prangi, this cetbang is a breech-loading swivel gun made of bronze or iron, firing single rounds or scattershots (a large number of small bullets).
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] Cannons derived from western-style cetbang can be found in Nusantara, among others were lantaka and lela.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] Most lantakas were made of bronze and the earliest ones were breech-loaded.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] There is a trend toward muzzle-loading weapons during colonial times.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] When the Portuguese came to the archipelago, they referred to the breech-loading swivel gun as *berço*, while the Spaniards call it *verso*.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] A pole gun (*bedil tombak*) was recorded as being used by Java in 1413.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] 1514 said that the inhabitants of Java were great masters in casting artillery and very good artillerymen.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] They made many one-pounder cannon (*cetbang* or *rentaka*), long muskets, *spingarde* (arquebus), *schioppi* (hand cannon), Greek fire, guns (cannon), and other fireworks.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] Every place was considered excellent in casting artillery, and in the knowledge of using it.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] In 1513, the Javanese fleet led by Pati Unus sailed to attack Portuguese Malacca "with much artillery made in Java, for the Javanese are skilled in founding and casting, and in all works in iron, over and above what they have in India".
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] By early 16th century, the Javanese already locally-producing large guns, some of them still survived until the present day and dubbed as "sacred cannon" or "holy cannon".
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] These cannons varied between 180- and 260-pounders, weighing anywhere between 3 and 8 tons, length of them between 3 and 6 m (9.8 and 19.7 ft).
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] Cannons were used by the Ayutthaya Kingdom in 1352 during its invasion of the Khmer Empire.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] Within a decade large quantities of gunpowder could be found in the Khmer Empire.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] By the end of the 14th century firearms were also used by the Trần dynasty.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] Saltpeter harvesting was recorded by Dutch and German travellers as being common in even the smallest villages and was collected from the decomposition process of large dung hills specifically piled for the purpose.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] The Dutch punishment for possession of non-permitted gunpowder appears to have been amputation.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] Ownership and manufacture of gunpowder was later prohibited by the colonial Dutch occupiers.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] According to colonel McKenzie quoted in Sir Thomas Stamford Raffles' *The History of Java* (1817), the purest sulfur was supplied from a crater from a mountain near the straits of Bali.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] In Africa, the Adal Sultanate and the Abyssinian Empire both deployed cannons during the Adal-Abyssinian War.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] Imported from Arabia, and the wider Islamic world, the Adalites led by Ahmed ibn Ibrahim al-Ghazi were the first African power to introduce cannon warfare to the African continent.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] Later on as the Portuguese Empire entered the war it would supply and train the Abyssinians with cannons, while the Ottoman Empire sent soldiers and cannon to back Adal.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] The conflict proved, through their use on both sides, the value of firearms such as the matchlock musket, cannon, and the arquebus over traditional weapons.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] While previous smaller guns could burn down structures with fire, larger and more powerful cannons forced engineers to develop stronger castle walls from enemy attacks.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] Cannons were used for other purposes, as fortifications began using cannons as defensive instruments.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] In India, the fort of Raicher had gun ports built into its walls to accommodate the use of defensive cannons.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] In *The Art of War*, Niccolò Machiavelli opined that field artillery forced an army to take up a defensive posture and opposed a more ideal offensive stance.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] Machiavelli's concerns can be seen in the criticisms of Portuguese mortars being used in India during the sixteenth century as lack of mobility was one of the key problems with the design.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] In Russia the early cannons were again placed in forts as a defensive tool.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p01] Cannons were also difficult to move around in mountainous regions; offensives conducted with such weapons would often be unsuccessful in areas such as Iran.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] By the 16th century, cannons were made in a great variety of lengths and bore diameters, but the general rule was that the longer the barrel, the longer the range.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] Some cannons made during this time had barrels exceeding 10 ft (3.0 m) in length, and could weigh up to 20,000 pounds (9,100 kg).
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] Consequently, large amounts of gunpowder were needed to allow them to fire stone balls several hundred yards.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] By mid-century, European monarchs began to classify cannons to reduce the confusion.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] Henry II of France opted for six sizes of cannon, but others settled for more; the Spanish used twelve sizes, and the English sixteen.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] They are, from largest to smallest: the cannon royal, cannon, cannon serpentine, bastard cannon, demicannon, pedrero, culverin, basilisk, demiculverin, bastard culverin, saker, minion, falcon, falconet, serpentine, and rabinet.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] Better powder had been developed by this time as well.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] Instead of the finely ground powder used by the first bombards, powder was replaced by a "corned" variety of coarse grains.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] This coarse powder had pockets of air between grains, allowing fire to travel through and ignite the entire charge quickly and uniformly.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] The end of the Middle Ages saw the construction of larger, more powerful cannon, as well as their spread throughout the world.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] As they were not effective at breaching the newer fortifications resulting from the development of cannon, siege engines—such as siege towers and trebuchets—became less widely used.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] However, wooden "battery-towers" took on a similar role as siege towers in the gunpowder age—such as that used at Siege of Kazan in 1552, which could hold ten large-calibre cannon, in addition to 50 lighter pieces.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] Another notable effect of cannon on warfare during this period was the change in conventional fortifications.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] Niccolò Machiavelli wrote, "There is no wall, whatever its thickness that artillery will not destroy in only a few days." Although castles were not immediately made obsolete by cannon, their use and importance on the battlefield rapidly declined.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] Instead of majestic towers and merlons, the walls of new fortresses were thick, angled, and sloped, while towers became low and stout; increasing use was also made of earth and brick in breastworks and redoubts.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] These new defences became known as bastion forts, after their characteristic shape which attempted to force any advance towards it directly into the firing line of the guns.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] A few of these featured cannon batteries, such as the House of Tudor's Device Forts in England.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] Bastion forts soon replaced castles in Europe and, eventually, those in the Americas as well.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] By the end of the 15th century, several technological advancements made cannons more mobile.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] Wheeled gun carriages and trunnions became common, and the invention of the limber further facilitated transportation.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] As a result, field artillery became more viable and began to see more widespread use, often alongside the larger cannons intended for sieges.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] Better gunpowder, cast-iron projectiles (replacing stone), and the standardisation of calibres meant that even relatively light cannons could be deadly.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] Despite the increased maneuverability, however, cannon were still the slowest component of the army: a heavy English cannon required 23 horses to transport, while a culverin needed nine.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] Even with this many animals pulling, they still moved at a walking pace.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] Due to their relatively slow speed, lack of organisation, and undeveloped tactics, the combination of pike and shot still dominated the battlefields of Europe.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] Innovations continued, notably the German invention of the mortar, a thick-walled, short-barrelled gun that blasted shot upward at a steep angle.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] Mortars were useful for sieges, as they could hit targets behind walls or other defences.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] This cannon found more use with the Dutch, who learnt to shoot bombs filled with powder from them.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] "Single firing" was first used to ignite the fuse, where the bomb was placed with the fuse down against the cannon's propellant.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] This often resulted in the fuse being blown into the bomb, causing it to blow up as it left the mortar.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] Because of this, "double firing" was tried where the gunner lit the fuse and then the touch hole.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] This required considerable skill and timing, and was especially dangerous if the gun misfired, leaving a lighted bomb in the barrel.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] Not until 1650 was it accidentally discovered that double-lighting was superfluous as the heat of firing would light the fuse.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] Gustavus Adolphus of Sweden emphasised the use of light cannon and mobility in his army, and created new formations and tactics that revolutionised artillery.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] He discontinued using all 12 pounder—or heavier—cannon as field artillery, preferring, instead, to use cannons that could be handled by only a few men.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] One obsolete type of gun, the "leatheren", was replaced by 4 pounder and 9 pounder demi-culverins.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] These could be operated by three men, and pulled by only two horses.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] Gustavus Adolphus's army was also the first to use a cartridge that contained both powder and shot which sped up reloading, increasing the rate of fire.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] Finally, against infantry he pioneered the use of canister shot—essentially a tin can filled with musket balls.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] Until then there was no more than one cannon for every thousand infantrymen on the battlefield but Gustavus Adolphus increased the number of cannons sixfold.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] Each regiment was assigned two pieces, though he often arranged them into batteries instead of distributing them piecemeal.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] He used these batteries to break his opponent's infantry line, while his cavalry would outflank their heavy guns.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] At the Battle of Breitenfeld, in 1631, Adolphus proved the effectiveness of the changes made to his army, by defeating Johann Tserclaes, Count of Tilly.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] Although severely outnumbered, the Swedes were able to fire between three and five times as many volleys of artillery, and their infantry's linear formations helped ensure they did not lose any ground.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] Battered by cannon fire, and low on morale, Tilly's men broke ranks and fled.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] In England, cannons were being used to besiege various fortified buildings during the English Civil War.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] Nathaniel Nye is recorded as testing a Birmingham cannon in 1643 and experimenting with a saker in 1645.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] From 1645 he was the master gunner to the Parliamentarian garrison at Evesham and in 1646 he successfully directed the artillery at the Siege of Worcester, detailing his experiences and in his 1647 book *The Art of Gunnery*.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] Believing that war was as much a science as an art, his explanations focused on triangulation, arithmetic, theoretical mathematics, and cartography as well as practical considerations such as the ideal specification for gunpowder or slow matches.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] His book acknowledged mathematicians such as Robert Recorde and Marcus Jordanus as well as earlier military writers on artillery such as Niccolò Fontana Tartaglia and Thomas (or Francis) Malthus (author of *A Treatise on Artificial Fire-Works*).
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] Around this time also came the idea of aiming the cannon to hit a target.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] Gunners controlled the range of their cannons by measuring the angle of elevation, using a "gunner's quadrant".
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] Cannons did not have sights; therefore, even with measuring tools, aiming was still largely guesswork.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] In the latter half of the 17th century, the French engineer Sébastien Le Prestre de Vauban introduced a more systematic and scientific approach to attacking gunpowder fortresses, in a time when many field commanders "were notorious dunces in siegecraft".
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] Careful sapping forward, supported by enfilading ricochets, was a key feature of this system, and it even allowed Vauban to calculate the length of time a siege would take.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] He was also a prolific builder of bastion forts, and did much to popularize the idea of "depth in defence" in the face of cannon.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] These principles were followed into the mid-19th century, when changes in armaments necessitated greater depth defence than Vauban had provided for.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] It was only in the years prior to World War I that new works began to break radically away from his designs.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] The lower tier of 17th-century English ships of the line were usually equipped with demi-cannons, guns that fired a 32-pound (15 kg) solid shot, and could weigh up to 3,400 pounds (1,500 kg).
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] Demi-cannons were capable of firing these heavy metal balls with such force that they could penetrate more than a metre of solid oak, from a distance of 90 m (300 ft), and could dismast even the largest ships at close range.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] Full cannon fired a 42-pound (19 kg) shot, but were discontinued by the 18th century, as they were too unwieldy.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] By the end of the 18th century, principles long adopted in Europe specified the characteristics of the Royal Navy's cannon, as well as the acceptable defects, and their severity.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] The United States Navy tested guns by measuring them, firing them two or three times—termed "proof by powder"—and using pressurized water to detect leaks.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] The carronade was adopted by the Royal Navy in 1779; the lower muzzle velocity of the round shot when fired from this cannon was intended to create more wooden splinters when hitting the structure of an enemy vessel, as they were believed to be more deadly than the ball by itself.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] The carronade was much shorter, and weighed between a third to a quarter of the equivalent long gun; for example, a 32-pounder carronade weighed less than a ton, compared with a 32-pounder long gun, which weighed over 3 t (3.0 long tons; 3.3 short tons).
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] The guns were, therefore, easier to handle, and also required less than half as much gunpowder, allowing fewer men to crew them.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] Carronades were manufactured in the usual naval gun calibres, but were not counted in a ship of the line's rated number of guns.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] As a result, the classification of Royal Navy vessels in this period can be misleading, as they often carried more cannons than were listed.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] Cannons were crucial in Napoleon's rise to power, and continued to play an important role in his army in later years.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] During the French Revolution, the unpopularity of the Directory led to riots and rebellions.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] When over 25,000 royalists led by General Danican assaulted Paris, Paul Barras was appointed to defend the capital; outnumbered five to one and disorganised, the Republicans were desperate.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] When Napoleon arrived, he reorganised the defences but realised that without cannons the city could not be held.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] He ordered Joachim Murat to bring the guns from the Sablons artillery park; the Major and his cavalry fought their way to the recently captured cannons, and brought them back to Napoleon.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] When Danican's poorly trained men attacked, on 13 Vendémiaire 1795 (5 October in the calendar used in France at the time), Napoleon ordered his cannon to fire grapeshot into the mob, an act that became known as the "whiff of grapeshot".
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] The slaughter effectively ended the threat to the new government, while, at the same time, making Bonaparte a famous—and popular—public figure.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] Among the first generals to recognise that artillery was not being used to its full potential, Napoleon often massed his cannon into batteries and introduced several changes into the French artillery, improving it significantly and making it among the finest in Europe.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] Such tactics were successfully used by the French, for example, at the Battle of Friedland, when 66 guns fired a total of 3,000 roundshot and 500 rounds of grapeshot, inflicting severe casualties to the Russian forces, whose losses numbered over 20,000 killed and wounded, in total.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] At the Battle of Waterloo—Napoleon's final battle—the French army had many more artillery pieces than either the British or Prussians.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] As the battlefield was muddy, recoil caused cannons to bury themselves into the ground after firing, resulting in slow rates of fire, as more effort was required to move them back into an adequate firing position; also, roundshot did not ricochet with as much force from the wet earth.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] Despite the drawbacks, sustained artillery fire proved deadly during the engagement, especially during the French cavalry attack.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] The British infantry, having formed infantry squares, took heavy losses from the French guns, while their own cannons fired at the cuirassiers and lancers, when they fell back to regroup.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] Eventually, the French ceased their assault, after taking heavy losses from the British cannon and musket fire.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] In the 1810s and 1820s, greater emphasis was placed on the accuracy of long-range gunfire, and less on the weight of a broadside.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] Around 1822, George Marshall wrote *Marshall's Practical Marine Gunnery*.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] The book was used by cannon operators in the United States Navy throughout the 19th century.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] It listed all the types of cannons and instructions.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] The carronade, although initially very successful and widely adopted, disappeared from the Royal Navy in the 1850s after the development of wrought-iron-jacketed steel cannon by William Armstrong and Joseph Whitworth.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] Nevertheless, carronades were used in the American Civil War.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] Western cannons during the 19th century became larger, more destructive, more accurate, and could fire at longer range.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] One example is the American 3-inch (76 mm) wrought-iron, muzzle-loading rifle, or Griffen gun (usually called the 3-inch Ordnance Rifle), used during the American Civil War, which had an effective range of over 1.1 mi (1.8 km).
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] Another is the smoothbore 12-pounder Napoleon, which originated in France in 1853 and was widely used by both sides in the American Civil War.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] This cannon was renowned for its sturdiness, reliability, firepower, flexibility, relatively lightweight, and range of 1,700 m (5,600 ft).
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] The practice of rifling—casting spiralling lines inside the cannon's barrel—was applied to artillery more frequently by 1855, as it gave cannon projectiles gyroscopic stability, which improved their accuracy.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] One of the earliest rifled cannons was the breech-loading Armstrong Gun—also invented by William Armstrong—which boasted significantly improved range, accuracy, and power than earlier weapons.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] The projectile fired from the Armstrong gun could reportedly pierce through a ship's side and explode inside the enemy vessel, causing increased damage and casualties.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] The British military adopted the Armstrong gun, and was impressed; the Duke of Cambridge even declared that it "could do everything but speak".
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] Despite being significantly more advanced than its predecessors, the Armstrong gun was rejected soon after its integration, in favour of the muzzle-loading pieces that had been in use before.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] While both types of gun were effective against wooden ships, neither had the capability to pierce the armour of ironclads; due to reports of slight problems with the breeches of the Armstrong gun, and their higher cost, the older muzzle-loaders were selected to remain in service instead.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] The superior cannon of the Western world brought them tremendous advantages in warfare.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] For example, in the First Opium War in China, during the 19th century, British battleships bombarded the coastal areas and fortifications from afar, safe from the reach of the Chinese cannons.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] Similarly, the shortest war in recorded history, the Anglo-Zanzibar War of 1896, was brought to a swift conclusion by shelling from British cruisers.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] Cannons in the 20th and 21st centuries are usually divided into sub-categories and given separate names.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] Some of the most widely used types of modern cannon are howitzers, mortars, guns, and autocannon, although a few very large-calibre cannon, custom-designed, have also been constructed.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] Nuclear artillery was experimented with, but was abandoned as impractical.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] Modern artillery is used in a variety of roles, depending on its type.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] According to NATO, the general role of artillery is to provide fire support, which is defined as "the application of fire, coordinated with the manoeuvre of forces to destroy, neutralize, or suppress the enemy".
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] When referring to cannons, the term *gun* is often used incorrectly.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] By the early 20th century, infantry weapons had become more powerful, forcing most artillery away from the front lines.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] Despite the change to indirect fire, cannons proved highly effective during World War I, directly or indirectly causing over 75% of casualties.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] The onset of trench warfare after the first few months of World War I greatly increased the demand for howitzers, as they were more suited to hitting targets in trenches.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] Furthermore, their shells carried more explosives than those of guns, and caused considerably less barrel wear.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] The German army had the advantage here as they began the war with many more howitzers than the French.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] World War I also saw the use of the Paris Gun, the longest-ranged gun ever fired.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] This 200 mm (8 in) calibre gun was used by the Germans against Paris and could hit targets more than 122 km (76 mi) away.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] The Second World War sparked new developments in cannon technology.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] Among them were sabot rounds, hollow-charge projectiles, and proximity fuses, all of which increased the effectiveness of cannon against specific targets.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] The proximity fuse emerged on the battlefields of Europe in late December 1944.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] Used to great effect in anti-aircraft projectiles, proximity fuses were fielded in both the European and Pacific Theatres of Operations; they were particularly useful against V-1 flying bombs and kamikaze planes.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] Although widely used in naval warfare, and in anti-air guns, both the British and Americans feared unexploded proximity fuses would be reverse engineered, leading to them limiting their use in continental battles.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] During the Battle of the Bulge, however, the fuses became known as the American artillery's "Christmas present" for the German army because of their effectiveness against German personnel in the open, when they frequently dispersed attacks.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] Anti-tank guns were also tremendously improved during the war: in 1939, the British used primarily 2 pounder and 6 pounder guns.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] By the end of the war, 17 pounders had proven much more effective against German tanks, and 32 pounders had entered development.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] Meanwhile, German tanks were continuously upgraded with better main guns, in addition to other improvements.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] For example, the Panzer III was originally designed with a 37 mm gun, but was mass-produced with a 50 mm cannon.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] To counter the threat of the Russian T-34s, another, more powerful 50 mm gun was introduced, only to give way to a larger 75 mm cannon, which was in a fixed mount as the StuG III, the most-produced German World War II armoured fighting vehicle of any type.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] Despite the improved guns, production of the Panzer III was ended in 1943, as the tank still could not match the T-34, and was replaced by the Panzer IV and Panther tanks.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] In 1944, the 8.8 cm KwK 43 and many variations, entered service with the Wehrmacht, and was used as both a tank main gun, and as the PaK 43 anti-tank gun.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] One of the most powerful guns to see service in World War II, it was capable of destroying any Allied tank at very long ranges.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] Despite being designed to fire at trajectories with a steep angle of descent, howitzers can be fired directly, as was done by the 11th Marine Regiment at the Battle of Chosin Reservoir, during the Korean War.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] Two field batteries fired directly upon a battalion of Chinese infantry; the Marines were forced to brace themselves against their howitzers, as they had no time to dig them in.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] The Chinese infantry took heavy casualties, and were forced to retreat.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] The tendency to create larger calibre cannons during the World Wars has reversed since.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] The United States Army, for example, sought a lighter, more versatile howitzer, to replace their aging pieces.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] As it could be towed, the M198 was selected to be the successor to the World War II–era cannons used at the time, and entered service in 1979.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] Still in use today, the M198 is, in turn, being slowly replaced by the M777 Ultralightweight howitzer, which weighs nearly half as much and can be more easily moved.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] Although land-based artillery such as the M198 are powerful, long-ranged, and accurate, naval guns have not been neglected, despite being much smaller than in the past, and, in some cases, having been replaced by cruise missiles.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] However, the *Zumwalt*-class destroyer's planned armament included the Advanced Gun System (AGS), a pair of 155 mm guns, which fire the Long Range Land-Attack Projectile.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] The warhead, which weighed 24 pounds (11 kg), had a circular error of probability of 50 m (160 ft), and was mounted on a rocket, to increase the effective range to 100 nmi (190 km), further than that of the Paris Gun.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] The AGS's barrels would be water-cooled, and fire 10 rounds per minute, per gun.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] The combined firepower from both turrets would give a *Zumwalt*-class destroyer the firepower equivalent to 12 conventional M198 howitzers.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] The reason for the re-integration of cannons as a main armament in United States Navy ships was because satellite-guided munitions fired from a gun would be less expensive than a cruise missile but have a similar guidance capability.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] Autocannons automatically fire a series of projectiles, similarly to a machine gun.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] They have mechanisms to automatically load their ammunition, and have a high rate of fire often approaching, or, in the case of rotary autocannons, even surpassing the firing rate of a machine gun.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] Autocannons are usually of larger calibre than machine guns, typically 20 mm (0.8 in) or greater, and can usually fire explosive shells, unlike machine guns.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] Explosive ammunition weighing less than 400 grams, as used by machine-gun calibres, is additionally banned in international conflict for parties to the Saint Petersburg Declaration of 1868.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] Most nations use rapid-fire cannon on light vehicles, instead of a more powerful, but heavier, tank gun with a low rate of fire.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] A typical autocannon is the 25 mm US "Bushmaster" chain gun, mounted on the LAV-25 and M2 Bradley armoured vehicles.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] The typical rate of fire for a modern autocannon ranges from 90 to 1,800 rounds per minute; systems with multiple barrels, such as rotary autocannon, can have rates of fire of several thousand rounds per minute.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] The fastest of these is the GSh-6-23, which has a rate of fire of over 10,000 rounds per minute.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] Autocannons are often fitted in aircraft and as shipboard anti-aircraft weapons, as they provide greater destructive power than previously-used machine guns.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] The first documented installation of a cannon firing explosive shells on an aircraft was on the Voisin Canon in 1911, displayed at the Paris Exposition that year.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] By World War I, all of the major powers were experimenting with aircraft-mounted cannons; however, their low rate of fire and great size and weight precluded any of them from being anything other than experimental.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] The most successful (or least unsuccessful) was the SPAD 12 Ca.1 single-seat fighter with a single 37 mm Puteaux mounted to fire between the cylinder banks and through the propeller boss of the aircraft's Hispano-Suiza 8C engine.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] The pilot (by necessity an ace) had to manually load one round at a time.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] The first autocannon were developed during World War I as anti-aircraft guns, and one of these, the Coventry Ordnance Works "COW 37 mm gun", was installed in an aircraft.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] However, the war ended before it could be given a field trial, and it never became standard equipment in a production aircraft.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] Later trials had it fixed at a steep angle upwards in both the Vickers Type 161 and the Westland C.O.W.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] Gun Fighter, an idea that returned later.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] During this period autocannons became available, and several fighters of the German *Luftwaffe* and the Imperial Japanese Navy Air Service were fitted with 20 mm cannons.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] They continued to be installed as an adjunct to machine guns rather than as a replacement, as the rate of fire was too low and each gun was too heavy.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] There was some debate in the RAF as to whether the greater number of possible rounds being fired from a machine gun, or a smaller number of explosive rounds from a cannon was preferable.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] Improvements during the war in regards to rate of fire allowed the cannon to displace the machine gun almost entirely.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] Cannons were more effective than machine-guns against armour, so they came increasingly into use in World War II; newer fighter aircraft such as the Hawker Tempest usually carried two or four instead of the six to twelve machine guns of earlier aircraft.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] The Hispano-Suiza HS.404, Oerlikon 20 mm cannon, MG FF, and their numerous variants became among the most widely used autocannon in the war.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] Aircraft cannons, as with machine guns, were either fixed to fire forwards (mounted in the wings, in the nose or fuselage, or in a pannier under either), typically on manoeuvrable fighters, or mounted movably in manned gun turrets on heavier less agile aircraft such as bombers.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] Both the Germans and Japanese mounted cannons to fire upwards and forwards for use against heavy bombers, with the Germans calling guns so-installed *Schräge Musik*, derived from a German colloquialism for jazz music—*schräg* means "off-key".
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] Nearly all modern fighter aircraft are armed with an autocannon, and they are also commonly fitted on ground-attack aircraft.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] One of the most powerful examples is the 30mm GAU-8/A Avenger Gatling-type rotary cannon mounted on the Fairchild Republic A-10 Thunderbolt II.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] The Lockheed AC-130 gunship, based on a transport aircraft, can carry a 105 mm howitzer and a variety of autocannons ranging up to 40 mm.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] Both are used in the close air support role.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] Cannons in general have the form of a truncated cone with an internal cylindrical bore for holding an explosive charge and a projectile.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] The thickest, strongest, and closed part of the cone is located near the explosive charge.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] As any explosive charge will dissipate in all directions equally, the thickest portion of the cannon is useful for containing and directing this force.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] Field artillery cannon in Europe and the Americas were initially made most often of bronze, though later forms were constructed of cast iron and eventually steel.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] However, cast-iron cannon have a tendency to burst without having shown any previous weakness or wear, and this makes them more dangerous to operate.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] The older and more-stable forms of cannon were muzzle-loading as opposed to breech-loading—to be used they had to have their ordnance packed down the bore through the muzzle rather than inserted through the breech.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] The following terms refer to the components or aspects of a classical western cannon (c.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] In what follows, the words *near*, *close*, and *behind* will refer to those parts towards the thick, closed end of the piece, and *far*, *front*, *in front of*, and *before* to the thinner, open end.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] is determined by the diameter of its bore.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] made of copper screwed into the length of the vent.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] The main body of a cannon consists of three basic extensions: the foremost and the longest is called the *chase*, the middle portion is the *reinforce*, and the closest and briefest portion is the *cascabel* or *cascable*.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] The chase is simply the entire conical part of the cannon in front of the *reinforce*.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] the narrowest part of the chase, always located near the foremost end of the piece.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] these are a second series of such rings located at the near end of the chase.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] To pack a muzzle-loading cannon, first gunpowder is poured down the bore.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] This is followed by a layer of wadding (often nothing more than paper), and then the cannonball itself.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] A certain amount of windage (in this case meaning that the bore is designed slightly wider than the cannonball) allows the ball to fit down the bore, though the greater the windage the less efficient the propulsion of the ball when the gunpowder is ignited.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] To fire the cannon, the fuse located in the vent is lit, quickly burning down to the gunpowder, which then explodes violently, propelling wadding and ball down the bore and out of the muzzle.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] A small portion of exploding gas also escapes through the vent, but this does not dramatically affect the total force exerted on the ball.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] *Gun* in this context specifically refers to a type of cannon that fires projectiles at high speeds, and usually at relatively low angles; they have been used in warships, and as field artillery.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] The term *cannon* is also used for autocannon, a modern repeating weapon firing explosive projectiles.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] Cannon have been used extensively in fighter aircraft since World War II.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] In the 1770s, cannon operation worked as follows: each cannon would be manned by two gunners, six soldiers, and four officers of artillery.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] The right gunner was to prime the piece and load it with powder, and the left gunner would fetch the powder from the magazine and be ready to fire the cannon at the officer's command.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] On each side of the cannon, three soldiers stood, to ram and sponge the cannon, and hold the ladle.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] The second soldier on the left was tasked with providing 50 bullets.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] Before loading, the cannon would be cleaned with a wet sponge to extinguish any smouldering material from the last shot.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] Fresh powder could be set off prematurely by lingering ignition sources.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] The powder was added, followed by wadding of paper or hay, and the ball was placed in and rammed down.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] After ramming, the cannon would be aimed with the elevation set using a quadrant and a plummet.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] At 45 degrees, the ball had the utmost range: about ten times the gun's level range.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] Any angle above a horizontal line was called random-shot.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] Wet sponges were used to cool the pieces every ten or twelve rounds.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] During the Napoleonic Wars, a British gun team consisted of five gunners to aim it, clean the bore with a damp sponge to quench any remaining embers before a fresh charge was introduced, and another to load the gun with a bag of powder and then the projectile.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] The fourth gunner pressed his thumb on the vent hole, to prevent a draught that might fan a flame.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] The charge loaded, the fourth would prick the bagged charge through the vent hole, and fill the vent with powder.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] On command, the fifth gunner would fire the piece with a slow match.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] Friction primers replaced slow match ignition by the mid-19th century.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] When a cannon had to be abandoned such as in a retreat or surrender, the touch hole of the cannon would be plugged flush with an iron spike, disabling the cannon (at least until metal boring tools could be used to remove the plug).
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] A gun was said to be *honeycombed* when the surface of the bore had cavities, or holes in it, caused by corrosion or casting defects.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] In the United States, muzzleloading cannons made before 1899 (and replicas) that are unable to fire fixed ammunition are considered antiques.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] They are not subject to the Gun Control Act of 1968 or National Firearms Act of 1934.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] They may be subject to local rules in some jurisdictions, however.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] Historically, logs or poles have been used as decoys to mislead the enemy as to the strength of an emplacement.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] The "Quaker Gun trick" was used by Colonel William Washington's Continental Army during the American Revolutionary War; in 1780, approximately 100 Loyalists surrendered to them, rather than face bombardment.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] During the American Civil War, Quaker guns were also used by the Confederates, to compensate for their shortage of artillery.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] The decoy cannon were painted black at the "muzzle", and positioned behind fortifications to delay Union attacks on those positions.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] On occasion, real gun carriages were used to complete the deception.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] Cannon sounds have sometimes been used in classical pieces with a military theme.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] One of the best known examples is Pyotr Ilyich Tchaikovsky's *1812 Overture*.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] The overture is to be performed using an artillery section together with the orchestra, resulting in noise levels high enough that musicians are required to wear ear protection.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] The cannon fire simulates Russian artillery bombardments of the Battle of Borodino, a critical battle in Napoleon's invasion of Russia, whose defeat the piece celebrates.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] When the overture was first performed, the cannon were fired by an electric current triggered by the conductor.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] However, the overture was not recorded with real cannon fire until Mercury Records and conductor Antal Doráti's 1958 recording of the Minnesota Orchestra.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] Cannon fire is also frequently used in presentations of the *1812* on American Independence Day, a tradition started by Arthur Fiedler of the Boston Pops in 1974.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] The hard rock band AC/DC used cannon fire in their song "For Those About to Rock (We Salute You)", and in live shows replica Napoleonic cannons and pyrotechnics were used to perform the piece.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] A recording of that song has accompanied the firing of an authentic reproduction of a M1857 12-pounder Napoleon during Columbus Blue Jackets goal celebrations at Nationwide Arena since opening night of the 2007–08 season.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] The cannon is the focal point of the team's alternate logo on its third jerseys.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] Cannons have been fired in touchdown celebrations by several American football teams including the San Diego Chargers.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] The Pittsburgh Steelers used one only during the 1962 campaign but discontinued it after Buddy Dial was startled by inadvertently running face-first into the cannon's smoky discharge in a 42–27 loss to the Dallas Cowboys.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] Cannon recovered from the sea are often extensively damaged from exposure to salt water; electrolytic reduction treatment is required to forestall corrosion.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] The cannon is then washed in deionized water to remove the electrolyte, and is treated in tannic acid, which prevents further rust and gives the metal a bluish-black colour.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] Cannon on display may be protected from oxygen and moisture by a wax sealant.
[src:broadside-naval/cannon-p02] A coat of polyurethane may also be painted over the wax sealant, to prevent the cannon from attracting dust.
[src:broadside-naval/carrack] A **carrack** (Portuguese: *nau*; Spanish: *nao*; Catalan: *carraca*) is a three- or four-masted ocean-going sailing ship that was developed in the 14th to 15th centuries in Europe, most notably in Portugal and Spain.
[src:broadside-naval/carrack] Evolving from the single-masted cog, the carrack was first used for European trade from the Mediterranean to the Baltic and quickly found use with the newly found wealth of the trade between Europe and Africa and then the trans-Atlantic trade with the Americas.
[src:broadside-naval/carrack] In their most advanced forms, they were used by the Portuguese and Spaniards for trade between Europe, Africa and Asia starting in the late 15th century, before being gradually superseded in the late 16th and early 17th centuries by the galleon.
[src:broadside-naval/carrack] In its most developed form, the carrack was a carvel-built ocean-going ship: large enough to be stable in heavy seas, and capacious enough to carry a large cargo and the provisions needed for very long voyages.
[src:broadside-naval/carrack] The later carracks were square-rigged on the foremast and mainmast and lateen-rigged on the mizzenmast.
[src:broadside-naval/carrack] They had a high rounded stern with aftcastle, forecastle and bowsprit at the stem.
[src:broadside-naval/carrack] As the predecessor of the galleon, the carrack was one of the most influential ship designs in history; while ships became more specialized in the following centuries, the basic design remained unchanged throughout this period.
[src:broadside-naval/carrack] English *carrack* was loaned in the late 14th century, via Old French *caraque*, from *carraca*, a term for a large, square-rigged sailing vessel used in Spanish, Italian and Middle Latin.
[src:broadside-naval/carrack] These ships were called *nau* in Portuguese, *carraca* in Genoese and Spanish, *caraque* or *nef* in French, and *kraak* in Dutch.
[src:broadside-naval/carrack] Its attestation in Greek literature is distributed in two closely related regions.
[src:broadside-naval/carrack] The first distribution region, or area, associates it with certain light and fast merchantmen found near Cyprus and Corfu.
[src:broadside-naval/carrack] The second is an extensive attestation in the Oxyrhynchus corpus, where it seems most frequently to describe the Nile barges of the Ptolemaic pharaohs.
[src:broadside-naval/carrack] Both of these usages may lead back through the Phoenician to the Akkadian *kalakku*, which denotes a type of river barge.
[src:broadside-naval/carrack] The Akkadian term is assumed to be derived from a Sumerian antecedent.
[src:broadside-naval/carrack] A modern reflex of the word is found in Arabic and Turkish *kelek* "raft; riverboat".
[src:broadside-naval/carrack] By the Late Middle Ages, the cog and cog-like square-rigged vessels equipped with a rudder at the stern, were widely used along the coasts of Europe, from the Mediterranean, to the Baltic.
[src:broadside-naval/carrack] Given the conditions of the Mediterranean, galley type vessels were extensively used there, as were various two masted vessels, including the caravels with their lateen sails.
[src:broadside-naval/carrack] These and similar ship types were familiar to Portuguese navigators and shipwrights.
[src:broadside-naval/carrack] As the Portuguese and Spaniards gradually extended their trade ever further south along Africa's Atlantic coast and islands during the 15th century, they needed larger, more durable and more advanced sailing ships for their long oceanic ventures.
[src:broadside-naval/carrack] In addition to the average tonnage naus, some naus (carracks) were also built in the reign of John II of Portugal, but were widespread only after the turn of the century.
[src:broadside-naval/carrack] The Portuguese carracks were usually very large ships for their time, often over 1000 tons displacement, and having the future naus of the India run and of the China and Japan trade, also other new types of design.
[src:broadside-naval/carrack] A typical three-masted carrack such as the *São Gabriel* had six sails: bowsprit, foresail, mainsail, mizzensail and two topsails.
[src:broadside-naval/carrack] In the Republic of Ragusa, a kind of a three or four masted carrack called *Dubrovačka karaka* (Dubrovnik Carrack) was used between the 14th and the 17th century for cargo transport.
[src:broadside-naval/carrack] In the middle of the 16th century, the first galleons were developed from the carrack.
[src:broadside-naval/carrack] The galleon design came to replace that of the carrack although carracks were still in use as late as the middle of the 17th century due to their larger cargo capacity.
[src:broadside-naval/carrack] Starting in 1498, Portugal initiated for the first time direct and regular exchanges between Europe and India—and the rest of Asia thereafter—through the Cape Route, a voyage that required the use of more substantial vessels, such as carracks, due to its unprecedented duration, about six months.
[src:broadside-naval/carrack] On average, four carracks connected Lisbon to Goa carrying gold to purchase spices and other exotic items, but mainly pepper.
[src:broadside-naval/carrack] From Goa, one carrack went on to Ming China in order to purchase silks.
[src:broadside-naval/carrack] In 1557 the Portuguese acquired Macau to develop this trade in partnership with the Chinese.
[src:broadside-naval/carrack] That trade continued with few interruptions until 1638, when it was prohibited by the rulers of Japan on the grounds that the ships were smuggling Catholic priests into the country.
[src:broadside-naval/carrack] The Japanese called Portuguese carracks "Black Ships" (*kurofune*), referring to the colour of the ship's hulls.
[src:broadside-naval/carrack] This term would eventually come to refer to any Western vessel, not just Portuguese.
[src:broadside-naval/carrack] The Islamic world also built and used carracks, or at least carrack-like ships, in the Mediterranean and the Indian Ocean.
[src:broadside-naval/carrack] A picture of an Ottoman *barca* on Piri Reis' map shows a deep-hulled ship with a tall forecastle and a lateen sail on the mizzenmast.
[src:broadside-naval/carrack] The *harraqa* (Saracen: *karaque*) was a type of ship used to hurl explosives or inflammable materials (firebomb in earthenware pots, naphtha, fire arrows).
[src:broadside-naval/carrack] From the context of Islamic texts, there are two types of *harraqa*: The cargo ship and the smaller longship (galley-like) that was used for fighting.
[src:broadside-naval/carrack] It is unclear whether the nomenclature *harraqa* has a connection with European *carraca* (carrack), or whether one influences the other.
[src:broadside-naval/carrack] One Muslim *harraqa* named *Mogarbina* was captured by the Knights of St.
[src:broadside-naval/carrack] John in 1507 from the Ottoman Turks and renamed *Santa Maria*.
[src:broadside-naval/carrack] Gujarati ships are usually called *naos* (carracks) by the Portuguese.
[src:broadside-naval/carrack] Gujarati *naos* operated between Malacca and the Red Sea, and were often larger than Portuguese carracks.
[src:broadside-naval/carrack] The Bengalis also used carracks, sometimes called *naos mauriscas* (Moorish carracks) by the Portuguese.
[src:broadside-naval/carrack] Arabs merchants of Mecca apparently used carracks too, since Duarte Barbosa noted that the Bengali people have "great *naos* after the fashion of Mecca".
[src:broadside-naval/carrack] The Italian word *caracca* and derivative words are popularly used in reference to a cumbersome individual, to an old vessel, or to a vehicle in a very bad condition.
[src:broadside-naval/carrack] The Portuguese form of "carrack", *nau*, is used as its unique unit in the *Civilization V* and *Civilization VI* strategy game.
